{"title_page": "Greyfriars Bobby (novel)", "text_new": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:''Greyfriars Bobby'' (novel)}}\n'''''Greyfriars Bobby''''' is a 1912 novel by [[Eleanor Atkinson]] based on the true story of the dog [[Greyfriars Bobby]]. The novel has been adapted into two films: ''[[Challenge to Lassie]]'' and ''[[Greyfriars Bobby (1961 film)|Greyfriars Bobby]]''. Both films starred [[Donald Crisp]]. The 1961 Walt Disney film ''[[Greyfriars Bobby: The True Story of a Dog]]'' was also based on this book.<ref>{{cite book |author=Douglas Brode |title=From Walt to Woodstock: How Disney Created the Counterculture |year=2004 |publisher=University of Texas Press |isbn=0-292-70273-6 |pages=194\u2013196}}</ref> This novel is written from the point-of-view of the dog, Bobby, and uses Scottish dialogue as the novel is set in [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]].{{Infobox novel\n| name         = Greyfriars Bobby\n| image        = Greyfriars bobby old cover.jpg\n| author       = [[Eleanor Atkinson]]\n| country      = [[United States]]\n| publisher    = [[A. L. Burt| A. L. Burt Company]]\n| release_date = 1912\n| media_type   = Print ([[Hardcover]])\n| pages        = 292\n}}\n\n==Plot==\n\nThe plot of ''Greyfriars Bobby'' is most unusual. The book is written from the mind of a dog, which makes every-day events very strange (a church clock becomes a \"time-gun\", for example). The main story of the book is directly adapted from the true Scottish story of [[Greyfriars Bobby]].\n\nBobby spends much time with his master and unofficial owner, \"Auld Jock\" ([[Scots]] for \"Old John\"), creating a very strong emotional connection. Though Jock never bought Bobby, they had an intense connection and Jock cared for Bobby very well. This creates problems later, because of Jock's having, in the eyes of the law, \"stolen\" an unlicensed dog. Eventually, Auld Jock dies. Bobby is obviously in great distress - but a loyal dog will never leave its owner's side, even after death.\n\nWhen his owner died, Bobby was lost - he could barely function without his companion. Since his owner's body was identified as John Gray and not Auld Jock, people still told Bobby to look for Jock, which just made the pain for Bobby worse. Bobby is lost for a while, and a large reward is offered for his return. Eventually, Bobby found his owner's grave and guarded it day and night - the pair is inseparable.<ref name=\"text\">{{cite web |last1=Atkinson |first1=Eleanor |title=Greyfriar's Bobby Text |url=https://www.gutenberg.org/files/2693/2693-h/2693-h.htm |website=The Project Gutenberg EBook of Greyfriars Bobby, by Eleanor Atkinson |publisher=Project Gutenberg |accessdate=13 February 2019 |ref=1}}</ref><ref name=\"lizzy\">{{cite web |last1=Siddal |first1=Lizzy |title=Greyfriars Bobby \u2013 Eleanor Atkinson |url=https://lizzysiddal.wordpress.com/2010/08/17/greyfriars-bobby-eleanor-atkinson/ |website=Lizzy\u2019s Literary Life |accessdate=13 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Characters==\n'''Bobby''' \n\nBobby is a Skye terrier from a heathery slope of the [[Pentland Hills]].<ref name=\"text\"/>\n\n'''Auld Jock'''\n\nAuld Jock is Bobby's owner.<ref name=\"text\"/>\n\nJock is Scottish for John, Auld is old so Old John.\n\n'''Mr. John Traill'''\n\nMr. John Traill is the owner of Ye Olde Greyfriars Dining-Rooms and a landlord.<ref name=\"text\"/>\n\n'''Sergeant Scott'''\n\nSergeant Scott is an officer of the Royal Engineers.<ref name=\"text\"/>\n\n'''Private McLean'''\n\nPrivate McLean is Sergeant Scott's private. McLean took care of Scott's belongings.<ref name=\"text\"/>\n\n'''James Brown'''\n\nJames Brown (or Mr. Brown) is the curator of the cemetery where Auld Jock was buried.<ref name=\"text\"/>\n\n'''Ailie and Tammy'''\n\nAilie and Tammy are children from the tenements of [[Edinburgh]].<ref name=\"text\"/>\n\n==Background==\n\nThis novel is based on the true Scottish story of [[Greyfriars Bobby]]. Prior to this 1912 novel, there were many conflicting accounts of the legend, due to inconsistencies being passed down through generations of Scottish families. [[Eleanor Atkinson]]'s novel served as a standardization and popularization of the story in the [[United States]]. Interestingly, Eleanor Atkinson had never stepped foot in Scotland in her life, but wrote extremely detailed depictions of landscapes of the region, implying that she was very familiar with the region through extensive research. Atkinson also very accurately depicts Scottish dialogue, a feat that suggests she wrote the book with the help of Scottish immigrants to the Midwest.<ref name=\"junior\">{{cite book |last1=Kunitz |first1=Stanley |editor1-last=Haycraft |editor1-first=Howard |title=The Junior Book of Authors: An Introduction to the Lives of Writers and Illustrators for Younger Readers, from Lewis Carroll and Louisa Alcott to the Present Day |date=1934 |publisher=H.W. Wilson Company |pages=400 |url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.b4512657;view=1up;seq=40}}</ref><ref name=\"pubweek\">{{cite book |last1=R.R. Bowker Company, Publishers' Board of Trade (U.S.), Book Trade Association of Philadelphia |first1=Am. Book Trade Association, American Book Trade Union |title=The Publishers Weekly, Volume 81, Part 1 |publisher=F. Leypoldt |page=664 |edition=1912 |accessdate=13 February 2019 |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=NBoDAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA664&lpg=PA664#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|Eh, laddie, I dinna ken what to do wi' ye. We maun juist hae to sleep oot.}}\n\nThe novel was on the market for 17 years, marketed at adults, before an illustrated children's version was released. Atkinson discusses how this is a result of the book being passed down from adults to their children, finding its way into schools' reading lists. She says the book was not written with a young audience in mind, and she credits this lack of simplification for younger audiences with the success of her work.<ref name='junior'></ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{wikisource|Greyfriar's Bobby|''Greyfriar's Bobby''}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1912 American novels]]\n[[Category:American novels adapted into films]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Novels about animals]]\n", "text_old": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:''Greyfriars Bobby'' (novel)}}\n'''''Greyfriars Bobby''''' is a 1912 novel by [[Eleanor Atkinson]] based on the true story of the dog [[Greyfriars Bobby]]. The novel has been adapted into two films: ''[[Challenge to Lassie]]'' and ''[[Greyfriars Bobby (1961 film)|Greyfriars Bobby]]''. Both films starred [[Donald Crisp]]. The 1961 Walt Disney film ''[[Greyfriars Bobby: The True Story of a Dog]]'' was also based on this book.<ref>{{cite book |author=Douglas Brode |title=From Walt to Woodstock: How Disney Created the Counterculture |year=2004 |publisher=University of Texas Press |isbn=0-292-70273-6 |pages=194\u2013196}}</ref> This novel is written from the point-of-view of the dog, Bobby, and uses Scottish dialogue as the novel is set in [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]].{{Infobox novel\n| name         = Greyfriars Bobby\n| image        = Greyfriars bobby old cover.jpg\n| author       = [[Eleanor Atkinson]]\n| country      = [[United States]]\n| publisher    = [[A. L. Burt| A. L. Burt Company]]\n| release_date = 1912\n| media_type   = Print ([[Hardcover]])\n| pages        = 292\n}}\n\n==Plot==\n\nThe plot of ''Greyfriars Bobby'' is very unique. The book is written from the mind of a dog, which makes every-day events very strange. The book references a church clock as a \"time-gun\", for example. The main story of the book is directly adapted from the true Scottish story of [[Greyfriars Bobby]]. Bobby spends a lot of time with his (unofficial) owner, Auld Jock (Scottish familiar name for Old John), creating a very strong emotional connection. Though Jock never bought Bobby, they had an intense connection and Jock cared for Bobby very well. This creates problems later due to the legality of Jocks's 'stealing' an unlicensed dog. Eventually, Auld Jock dies. Bobby is obviously in great distress - but a loyal dog will never leave their owner's side, even after death. When his owner died, Bobby was lost - he could barely function without his companion. Since his owner's body was identified as John Gray and not Auld Jock, people still told Bobby to look for Jock, which just made the pain for Bobby worse. Bobby is lost for a while, and a large reward is offered for his return Eventually, Bobby found his owner's grave and guarded it day and night - the pair is inseparable.<ref name=\"text\">{{cite web |last1=Atkinson |first1=Eleanor |title=Greyfriar's Bobby Text |url=https://www.gutenberg.org/files/2693/2693-h/2693-h.htm |website=The Project Gutenberg EBook of Greyfriars Bobby, by Eleanor Atkinson |publisher=Project Gutenberg |accessdate=13 February 2019 |ref=1}}</ref><ref name=\"lizzy\">{{cite web |last1=Siddal |first1=Lizzy |title=Greyfriars Bobby \u2013 Eleanor Atkinson |url=https://lizzysiddal.wordpress.com/2010/08/17/greyfriars-bobby-eleanor-atkinson/ |website=Lizzy\u2019s Literary Life |accessdate=13 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Characters==\n'''Bobby''' \n\nBobby is a Skye terrier from a heathery slope of the [[Pentland Hills]].<ref name=\"text\"/>\n\n'''Auld Jock'''\n\nAuld Jock is Bobby's owner.<ref name=\"text\"/>\n\nJock is Scottish for John, Auld is old so Old John.\n\n'''Mr. John Traill'''\n\nMr. John Traill is the owner of Ye Olde Greyfriars Dining-Rooms and a landlord.<ref name=\"text\"/>\n\n'''Sergeant Scott'''\n\nSergeant Scott is an officer of the Royal Engineers.<ref name=\"text\"/>\n\n'''Private McLean'''\n\nPrivate McLean is Sergeant Scott's private. McLean took care of Scott's belongings.<ref name=\"text\"/>\n\n'''James Brown'''\n\nJames Brown (or Mr. Brown) is the curator of the cemetery where Auld Jock was buried.<ref name=\"text\"/>\n\n'''Ailie and Tammy'''\n\nAilie and Tammy are children from the tenements of [[Edinburgh]].<ref name=\"text\"/>\n\n==Background==\n\nThis novel is based on the true Scottish story of [[Greyfriars Bobby]]. Prior to this 1912 novel, there were many conflicting accounts of the legend, due to inconsistencies being passed down through generations of Scottish families. [[Eleanor Atkinson]]'s novel served as a standardization and popularization of the story in the [[United States]]. Interestingly, Eleanor Atkinson had never stepped foot in Scotland in her life, but wrote extremely detailed depictions of landscapes of the region, implying that she was very familiar with the region through extensive research. Atkinson also very accurately depicts Scottish dialogue, a feat that suggests she wrote the book with the help of Scottish immigrants to the Midwest.<ref name=\"junior\">{{cite book |last1=Kunitz |first1=Stanley |editor1-last=Haycraft |editor1-first=Howard |title=The Junior Book of Authors: An Introduction to the Lives of Writers and Illustrators for Younger Readers, from Lewis Carroll and Louisa Alcott to the Present Day |date=1934 |publisher=H.W. Wilson Company |pages=400 |url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.b4512657;view=1up;seq=40}}</ref><ref name=\"pubweek\">{{cite book |last1=R.R. Bowker Company, Publishers' Board of Trade (U.S.), Book Trade Association of Philadelphia |first1=Am. Book Trade Association, American Book Trade Union |title=The Publishers Weekly, Volume 81, Part 1 |publisher=F. Leypoldt |page=664 |edition=1912 |accessdate=13 February 2019 |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=NBoDAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA664&lpg=PA664#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|Eh, laddie, I dinna ken what to do wi' ye. We maun juist hae to sleep oot.}}\n\nThe novel was on the market for 17 years, marketed at adults, before an illustrated children's version was released. Atkinson discusses how this is a result of the book being passed down from adults to their children, finding its way into schools' reading lists. She says the book was not written with a young audience in mind, and she credits this lack of simplification for younger audiences with the success of her work.<ref name='junior'></ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{wikisource|Greyfriar's Bobby|''Greyfriar's Bobby''}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1912 American novels]]\n[[Category:American novels adapted into films]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Novels about animals]]\n", "name_user": "Firstorm", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlot:Errors of grammar (\"a dog ... their\") and vocabulary (\"very unique\" -- \"unique\" is an absolute, not a synonym for \"unusual\" or \"rare\") corrected, infelicitous language modified.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greyfriars_Bobby_(novel)"}
{"title_page": "Tonga language (Zambia and Zimbabwe)", "text_new": "{{redirect|Chitonga|the chiTonga language of Malawi|Tonga (Nyasa) language|other languages called \"Tonga\"|Tonga language (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox language\n|name=Tonga \n|altname=Zambezi\n|nativename=''Chitonga''\n|states=[[Zambia]], [[Zimbabwe]]\n|ethnicity=[[Tonga people of Zambia and Zimbabwe|Tonga]], [[Kafwe Twa]]?\n|speakers={{sigfig|1.463<!--subtracting 4k for Shanjo & Kafwe Twa-->|2}} million\n|date=2001\u20132010 census\n|ref=e18\n|familycolor=Niger-Congo\n|fam2=[[Atlantic\u2013Congo languages|Atlantic\u2013Congo]]\n|fam3=[[Benue\u2013Congo languages|Benue\u2013Congo]]\n|fam4=[[Bantoid languages|Bantoid]]\n|fam5=[[Bantu languages|Bantu]]\n|fam6=[[Botatwe languages|Botatwe]]\n|nation=[[Zimbabwe]]\n|minority=[[Zambia]]\n|script=[[Latin script|Latin]] (Tonga alphabet)<br/>[[Tonga Braille]]\n|iso3=toi\n|lc1=dov |ld1=Dombe\n|guthrie=M.64\n|dia1=Plateau Tonga\n|dia2=Valley Tonga (We)\n|dia3=Leya\n|dia4=Mala\n|dia5=Ndawe\n|dia6=Dombe\n|glotto=tong1318\n|glottoname=Tonga\n|glottorefname=Tonga (Zambia)\n|glotto2=domb1246\n|glottoname2=Toka-Leya-Dombe\n}}\n\n'''Tonga''' (''Chitonga''), also known as ''Zambezi'', is a [[Bantu language]] primarily spoken by the [[Tonga people of Zambia and Zimbabwe|Tonga people]] who live mainly in the Southern and Western provinces of [[Zambia]], and in northern [[Zimbabwe]], with a few in [[Mozambique]]. The language is also spoken by the [[Tokaleya|Iwe, Toka and Leya people]], and perhaps by the [[Kafwe Twa]] (if they are not [[Ila language|Ila]]), as well as many bilingual Zambians and Zimbabweans. In Zambia Chitonga is taught in schools as first language in the whole of Southern Province, and parts of Lusaka and Central Provinces.\n\nIt is one of the major [[lingua franca]]s in Zambia, together with [[Bemba language|Bemba]], [[Lozi language|Lozi]] and [[Nyanja]]. The [[Tonga language (Malawi)|Tonga of Malawi]], which is classified by [[Guthrie classification of Bantu languages|Guthrie]] as belonging to zone N15, is not particularly close to Zambian Tonga, which is classified as zone M64, and can be considered a separate language.\n\nThe Tonga-speaking inhabitants are the oldest Bantu settlers, with the [[Tumbuka people|Tumbuka]], a small ethnic group in the east, in what is now known as Zambia. There are two distinctive dialects of Tonga; Valley Tonga and Plateau Tonga.  Valley Tonga is mostly spoken in the [[Zambezi]] valley and southern areas of the Batonga (Tonga people) while Plateau Tonga is spoken more around [[Monze District]] and the northern areas of the Batonga.<ref>A Practical Introduction to Chitonga, C.R. Hopgood, 1992 Edition, Zambia Educational Publishing House, p. x</ref>\n\nTonga (Chitonga or iciTonga) developed as a spoken language and was not put into written form until missionaries arrived in the area. The language is not standardized, and speakers of the same dialect may have different spellings for the same words once put into written text.<ref>Mweenzu Wafwulwe Ulalila Bowa (An Advanced Chitonga Language Course), R.N. Moonga and F.W. Wafer, Zambia Educational Publishing House, 1997, p. v</ref>\n\nAt least some speakers have a [[bilabial nasal click]] where neighboring dialects have /mw/, as in ''mwana'' 'child' and ''kumwa'' 'to drink'.<ref>Norval Smith, [[Harry van der Hulst]], 1988. ''Features, Segmental Structure & Harmony Processes,'' vol. 1 p. 198</ref>\n\nMaho (2009) removes [[Shanjo language|Shanjo]] as a separate, and not very closely related, language.\n\n==Verbs==\nTonga or Chitonga follows the standard [[Bantu languages#Language structure|Bantu language structure]]. A single word may incorporate a subject-marker, a tense-marker, a direct object, and even an indirect object, combined with the verb root itself.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Tense<ref>Tenses taken from Peace Corps Zambia Trainee's Book: Tonga, 2003</ref>\n! Tense marker\n! Example\n|-\n|\n| Subject-(tense marker)-verb root-(ending)\n|First person \"ndi\" doing something s/he shouldn't be doing \"kukuta\"\n|-\n| Present Simple\n| -(verb root)\n| Ndakuta\n|-\n| Present Perfect\n| -a-(verb root)-ide\n| Ndikutide\n|-\n| Present Continuous\n| -la-\n| Ndilakuta\n|-\n| Habitual Present Tense\n| -la-(verb root)-a\n| Ndilakuta\n|-\n| Recent Past (Past of Today)\n| -ali-(verb root)-ide\n| ndalikutide\n|-\n| Simple Past\n| -aka-\n| ndakakuta\n|-\n| Recent Past Continuous\n| -ali-ku-(verb root)\n| ndalikukuta\n|-\n| Habitual Past Continuous\n| -akali-ku-(verb root)\n| Ndakalikukuta\n|-\n| Remote Past\n| -aka-\n| ndakakuta\n|-\n| Near Future\n| -la-\n| Ndilakuta\n|-\n| Simple Future\n| -ya-ku-(verb root)-a\n| Ndiyakukuta\n|-\n| Future Habitual\n| -niku-(verb root)-a\n| ndinikukuta\n|-\n| Extended Future (Tomorrow or after tomorrow)\n| -yaku-(verb)-a\n| ndiyakukuta\n|}\n\n==Tonal system==\nTonga is a [[tone (linguistics)|tonal]] language, with high and low-toned syllables. The placement of the tones is complex and differs from that of other Bantu languages; for example, a syllable which is low in Tonga may be high in the cognate word in other Bantu languages and vice versa.<ref name=Gold>Goldsmith, John (1984) [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/248111984_Tone_and_accent_in_Tonga \"Tone and Accent in Tonga\"]. In Clements, G. N. and John Goldsmith ''Autosegmental Studies in Bantu Tone''. Dordrecht, Foris Publications, p. 48.</ref> Several scholars, beginning with [[A. E. Meeussen]] in 1963,<ref>Meeussen, A.E. (1963) \"Morphotonology of the Tonga Verb\", ''Journal of African Linguistics'' Vol.2, Part I.</ref> have tried to discover the rules for where to place the tones. \n\nOne feature of the tonal system is that high tones tend to get disassociated from their original place and move to the left, as is illustrated in these examples:<ref>Pulleyblank (1983) [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/36089880_Tone_in_lexical_phonology ''Tone in Lexical Phonology''], Massachusetts Institute of Technology, p. 191.</ref>\n*'''''\u00ed'''b'''\u00fa'''si'' 'smoke'\n*''ibusu'' 'flour'\n\nIn these words, the original high tone of the root ''-s\u00ed'' has moved to the prefix ''ibu-'', whereas the low tone of ''-su'' has not affected the prefix.\n\nThe above example of a noun is relatively easy to explain. However, the tones of the verbal system are more complex. An example of one of the puzzles discussed by both [[A. E. Meeussen|Meeussen]] and [[John Goldsmith (linguist)|Goldsmith]] can be seen below:\n\n*''ndi-la-lang-a'' 'I look at'\n*''ba-la-lang-a'' 'they look at'\n*''ndi-la-bon-a'' 'I see'\n*''ba-l'''\u00e1'''-bon-a'' 'they see'\n\nThe high tone on the tense-marker ''la'' in the fourth verb is puzzling. If it comes from the verb root ''bon'', it is hard to see why it does not also appear in the 1st person ''ndi-la-bon-a''. \n\nSome scholars, such as [[Hazel Carter (linguist)|Carter]]<ref>Carter, Hazel (1971) and (1972). \"Morphotonology of Zambian Tonga: Some Developments of Meeussen's System\". ''African Language Studies'' 12: 1-30 and 14: 36-52.</ref> and [[John Goldsmith (linguist)|Goldsmith]],<ref name=Gold /> have analysed Tonga as having both tones and accents (the accents in Tonga being mainly on low-toned syllables). Others, such as Pulleyblank, analyse the same data purely in terms of tonal rules, without the need to introduce accents.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wiktionarycat|category=Tonga (Zambia) language|type=the Tonga language of Zambia}}\n*[http://www.unhchr.ch/udhr/lang/toi.htm Universal Declaration of Human Rights in Chitonga]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110723165514/http://www.pinecity.k12.mn.us/elemschool/jscholin/Travel/Annie/chitonga.htm Glossary of Chitonga, in English and German]\n*[http://www.servus.at/argezim/tongatalk.htm Chitonga Glossary]\n*[http://www.language-archives.org/language/toi OLAC resources in and about the Tonga language]\n*[http://www.language-archives.org/language/dov OLAC resources in and about the Dombe language]\n*[http://lubutocollections.org/items/browse?search=Chitonga&submit_search=Search Chitonga language books]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, Lubuto Library Special Collections\n\n{{Pygmy languages}}\n{{Languages of Zambia}}\n{{Languages of Zimbabwe}}\n{{Languages of Mozambique}}\n{{Narrow Bantu languages|J-M}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Tonga ethnic group (Zambia and Zimbabwe)| ]]\n[[Category:Botatwe languages]]\n[[Category:Languages of Mozambique]]\n[[Category:Languages of Zambia]]\n[[Category:Languages of Zimbabwe]]\n[[Category:Library of Congress Africa Collection related]]\n[[Category:Tonal languages]]\n[[Category:Tone (linguistics)]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Chitonga|the chiTonga language of Malawi|Tonga (Nyasa) language|other languages called \"Tonga\"|Tonga language (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox language\n|name=Tonga \n|altname=Zambezi\n|nativename=''Chitonga''\n|states=[[Zambia]], [[Zimbabwe]]\n|ethnicity=[[Tonga people of Zambia and Zimbabwe|Tonga]], [[Kafwe Twa]]?\n|speakers={{sigfig|1.463<!--subtracting 4k for Shanjo & Kafwe Twa-->|2}} million\n|date=2001\u20132010 census\n|ref=e18\n|familycolor=Niger-Congo\n|fam2=[[Atlantic\u2013Congo languages|Atlantic\u2013Congo]]\n|fam3=[[Benue\u2013Congo languages|Benue\u2013Congo]]\n|fam4=[[Bantoid languages|Bantoid]]\n|fam5=[[Bantu languages|Bantu]]\n|fam6=[[Botatwe languages|Botatwe]]\n|nation=[[Zambia]]\n|minority=[[Zimbabwe]]\n|script=[[Latin script|Latin]] (Tonga alphabet)<br/>[[Tonga Braille]]\n|iso3=toi\n|lc1=dov |ld1=Dombe\n|guthrie=M.64\n|dia1=Plateau Tonga\n|dia2=Valley Tonga (We)\n|dia3=Leya\n|dia4=Mala\n|dia5=Ndawe\n|dia6=Dombe\n|glotto=tong1318\n|glottoname=Tonga\n|glottorefname=Tonga (Zambia)\n|glotto2=domb1246\n|glottoname2=Toka-Leya-Dombe\n}}\n\n'''Tonga''' (''Chitonga''), also known as ''Zambezi'', is a [[Bantu language]] primarily spoken by the [[Tonga people of Zambia and Zimbabwe|Tonga people]] who live mainly in the Southern and Western provinces of [[Zambia]], and in northern [[Zimbabwe]], with a few in [[Mozambique]]. The language is also spoken by the [[Tokaleya|Iwe, Toka and Leya people]], and perhaps by the [[Kafwe Twa]] (if they are not [[Ila language|Ila]]), as well as many bilingual Zambians and Zimbabweans. In Zambia Chitonga is taught in schools as first language in the whole of Southern Province, and parts of Lusaka and Central Provinces.\n\nIt is one of the major [[lingua franca]]s in Zambia, together with [[Bemba language|Bemba]], [[Lozi language|Lozi]] and [[Nyanja]]. The [[Tonga language (Malawi)|Tonga of Malawi]], which is classified by [[Guthrie classification of Bantu languages|Guthrie]] as belonging to zone N15, is not particularly close to Zambian Tonga, which is classified as zone M64, and can be considered a separate language.\n\nThe Tonga-speaking inhabitants are the oldest Bantu settlers, with the [[Tumbuka people|Tumbuka]], a small ethnic group in the east, in what is now known as Zambia. There are two distinctive dialects of Tonga; Valley Tonga and Plateau Tonga.  Valley Tonga is mostly spoken in the [[Zambezi]] valley and southern areas of the Batonga (Tonga people) while Plateau Tonga is spoken more around [[Monze District]] and the northern areas of the Batonga.<ref>A Practical Introduction to Chitonga, C.R. Hopgood, 1992 Edition, Zambia Educational Publishing House, p. x</ref>\n\nTonga (Chitonga or iciTonga) developed as a spoken language and was not put into written form until missionaries arrived in the area. The language is not standardized, and speakers of the same dialect may have different spellings for the same words once put into written text.<ref>Mweenzu Wafwulwe Ulalila Bowa (An Advanced Chitonga Language Course), R.N. Moonga and F.W. Wafer, Zambia Educational Publishing House, 1997, p. v</ref>\n\nAt least some speakers have a [[bilabial nasal click]] where neighboring dialects have /mw/, as in ''mwana'' 'child' and ''kumwa'' 'to drink'.<ref>Norval Smith, [[Harry van der Hulst]], 1988. ''Features, Segmental Structure & Harmony Processes,'' vol. 1 p. 198</ref>\n\nMaho (2009) removes [[Shanjo language|Shanjo]] as a separate, and not very closely related, language.\n\n==Verbs==\nTonga or Chitonga follows the standard [[Bantu languages#Language structure|Bantu language structure]]. A single word may incorporate a subject-marker, a tense-marker, a direct object, and even an indirect object, combined with the verb root itself.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Tense<ref>Tenses taken from Peace Corps Zambia Trainee's Book: Tonga, 2003</ref>\n! Tense marker\n! Example\n|-\n|\n| Subject-(tense marker)-verb root-(ending)\n|First person \"ndi\" doing something s/he shouldn't be doing \"kukuta\"\n|-\n| Present Simple\n| -(verb root)\n| Ndakuta\n|-\n| Present Perfect\n| -a-(verb root)-ide\n| Ndikutide\n|-\n| Present Continuous\n| -la-\n| Ndilakuta\n|-\n| Habitual Present Tense\n| -la-(verb root)-a\n| Ndilakuta\n|-\n| Recent Past (Past of Today)\n| -ali-(verb root)-ide\n| ndalikutide\n|-\n| Simple Past\n| -aka-\n| ndakakuta\n|-\n| Recent Past Continuous\n| -ali-ku-(verb root)\n| ndalikukuta\n|-\n| Habitual Past Continuous\n| -akali-ku-(verb root)\n| Ndakalikukuta\n|-\n| Remote Past\n| -aka-\n| ndakakuta\n|-\n| Near Future\n| -la-\n| Ndilakuta\n|-\n| Simple Future\n| -ya-ku-(verb root)-a\n| Ndiyakukuta\n|-\n| Future Habitual\n| -niku-(verb root)-a\n| ndinikukuta\n|-\n| Extended Future (Tomorrow or after tomorrow)\n| -yaku-(verb)-a\n| ndiyakukuta\n|}\n\n==Tonal system==\nTonga is a [[tone (linguistics)|tonal]] language, with high and low-toned syllables. The placement of the tones is complex and differs from that of other Bantu languages; for example, a syllable which is low in Tonga may be high in the cognate word in other Bantu languages and vice versa.<ref name=Gold>Goldsmith, John (1984) [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/248111984_Tone_and_accent_in_Tonga \"Tone and Accent in Tonga\"]. In Clements, G. N. and John Goldsmith ''Autosegmental Studies in Bantu Tone''. Dordrecht, Foris Publications, p. 48.</ref> Several scholars, beginning with [[A. E. Meeussen]] in 1963,<ref>Meeussen, A.E. (1963) \"Morphotonology of the Tonga Verb\", ''Journal of African Linguistics'' Vol.2, Part I.</ref> have tried to discover the rules for where to place the tones. \n\nOne feature of the tonal system is that high tones tend to get disassociated from their original place and move to the left, as is illustrated in these examples:<ref>Pulleyblank (1983) [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/36089880_Tone_in_lexical_phonology ''Tone in Lexical Phonology''], Massachusetts Institute of Technology, p. 191.</ref>\n*'''''\u00ed'''b'''\u00fa'''si'' 'smoke'\n*''ibusu'' 'flour'\n\nIn these words, the original high tone of the root ''-s\u00ed'' has moved to the prefix ''ibu-'', whereas the low tone of ''-su'' has not affected the prefix.\n\nThe above example of a noun is relatively easy to explain. However, the tones of the verbal system are more complex. An example of one of the puzzles discussed by both [[A. E. Meeussen|Meeussen]] and [[John Goldsmith (linguist)|Goldsmith]] can be seen below:\n\n*''ndi-la-lang-a'' 'I look at'\n*''ba-la-lang-a'' 'they look at'\n*''ndi-la-bon-a'' 'I see'\n*''ba-l'''\u00e1'''-bon-a'' 'they see'\n\nThe high tone on the tense-marker ''la'' in the fourth verb is puzzling. If it comes from the verb root ''bon'', it is hard to see why it does not also appear in the 1st person ''ndi-la-bon-a''. \n\nSome scholars, such as [[Hazel Carter (linguist)|Carter]]<ref>Carter, Hazel (1971) and (1972). \"Morphotonology of Zambian Tonga: Some Developments of Meeussen's System\". ''African Language Studies'' 12: 1-30 and 14: 36-52.</ref> and [[John Goldsmith (linguist)|Goldsmith]],<ref name=Gold /> have analysed Tonga as having both tones and accents (the accents in Tonga being mainly on low-toned syllables). Others, such as Pulleyblank, analyse the same data purely in terms of tonal rules, without the need to introduce accents.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wiktionarycat|category=Tonga (Zambia) language|type=the Tonga language of Zambia}}\n*[http://www.unhchr.ch/udhr/lang/toi.htm Universal Declaration of Human Rights in Chitonga]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110723165514/http://www.pinecity.k12.mn.us/elemschool/jscholin/Travel/Annie/chitonga.htm Glossary of Chitonga, in English and German]\n*[http://www.servus.at/argezim/tongatalk.htm Chitonga Glossary]\n*[http://www.language-archives.org/language/toi OLAC resources in and about the Tonga language]\n*[http://www.language-archives.org/language/dov OLAC resources in and about the Dombe language]\n*[http://lubutocollections.org/items/browse?search=Chitonga&submit_search=Search Chitonga language books]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, Lubuto Library Special Collections\n\n{{Pygmy languages}}\n{{Languages of Zambia}}\n{{Languages of Zimbabwe}}\n{{Languages of Mozambique}}\n{{Narrow Bantu languages|J-M}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Tonga ethnic group (Zambia and Zimbabwe)| ]]\n[[Category:Botatwe languages]]\n[[Category:Languages of Mozambique]]\n[[Category:Languages of Zambia]]\n[[Category:Languages of Zimbabwe]]\n[[Category:Library of Congress Africa Collection related]]\n[[Category:Tonal languages]]\n[[Category:Tone (linguistics)]]\n", "name_user": "Alexander 8620", "label": "safe", "comment": "Official in Zimbabwe, minority in Zambia.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tonga_language_(Zambia_and_Zimbabwe)"}
{"title_page": "Music (JoJo song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Music.\n| cover      = \n| alt        =\n| type       = [[Promotional single]]\n| artist     = [[JoJo (singer)|JoJo]]\n| album      = [[Mad Love (JoJo album)|Mad Love.]]\n| B-side     = \n| released   = {{Start date|2016|10|07}}\n| format     =\n* [[Music download|Digital download]]\n* [[Streaming media|Streaming]]\n| recorded   = 2016\n| studio     = [[Westlake Studios]]\n| genre      =\n* [[Pop music|Pop]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n| length     = 3:35\n| label      = \n*[[Atlantic Records]]\n| writer      =\n* [[JoJo (singer)|Joanna Levesque]]\n*Jussi Karvinen\n*[[Hayley Warner]]\n*[[Justin Tranter]]\n| producer   =\n* Jussifer\n| misc     = {{External music video|{{YouTube|0m4xsDviZQM|\"Music.\"}}|type=song}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Music.'''\"  is a song by American [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] singer-songwriter [[JoJo (singer)|JoJo]] from her third studio album ''[[Mad Love (JoJo album)|Mad Love.]]'' (2016). It was written by [[JoJo (singer)|Joanna Levesque]], Jussi Karvinen, [[Hayley Warner]] and [[Justin Tranter]], while the songs production was helmed by Jussifer. The song was released as the third and final promotional single from the album on October 7, 2016.<ref name=\"rap-up1\">https://www.rap-up.com/2016/10/06/video-jojo-music/</ref> Sonically, \"Music.\" is a piano driven [[pop ballad]] with [[contemporary R&B|R&B]] influences. Lyrically, the song is a vivid storytelling of JoJo's upbringing, growth, her love for music and family, including and ode to JoJo's father Joel Levesque who passed away in November 2015, while JoJo was in early recording sessions for the album.<ref name=\"rap-up2\">https://www.rap-up.com/rap-up-tv/jojo-talks-mad-love-kehlani-chance-the-rapper/</ref>\n\nThe song received generally positive reviews from contemporary music critics, with many praising the songs emotional weight and JoJo's raw vocal performance. JoJo dedicated the song to her father and links to the subject matter spoken about in her song \"Save my Soul\" from her \"''[[III (JoJo EP)|Tringle]]''\" (2015) EP. The song's accompanying music video premiered on JoJo's official [[YouTube]] channel on October 7, 2016, it consisted of clips of JoJo performing on stage, recording in studio, and doing interviews as a toddler as well as footage of her parents in a [[VHS]] style video. In promotion for her third album, \"Music.\" was included in the set list for JoJo's [[Mad Love Tour|Mad Love World Tour]].\n\n== Background ==\nThe song was originally titled \"Who Would I Be\" during the writing and recording process, JoJo opted to change the title to \"Music\" as the overall subject of the song related to music being her first love.<ref name=\"BMI Credits\">Title\u2013 ''Music''. [[Broadcast Music, Inc.]] BMI Work Number: 21885299.</ref> During the recording process for ''[[Mad Love (JoJo album)|Mad Love.]]'' (2016), \"Music.\" was the \"most personal\" and \"most difficult\" song to write and record for JoJo while serving as the opening song in the albums sequence.<ref name=\"iheart1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.iheart.com/content/2016-10-14-jojo-on-new-album-mad-love-details-alessia-cara-remy-ma-collabs/ |title=INTERVIEW: JoJo On New Album 'Mad Love.' &#124; iHeartRadio |publisher=Iheart.com |date=2016-10-14 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref name=\"rap-up2\" /> The song has been described as \"autobiographical\" and \"soul-searching\" along with \"I Am\", a song that closes up the standard edition of ''Mad Love''.<ref name=\"thefader1\">{{cite web|last=Myers |first=Owen |url=https://www.thefader.com/2016/10/12/jojo-interview-mad-love |title=How JoJo Found Her Voice, Again |publisher=The Fader |date=2016-10-12 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> In an interview with TheFader, JoJo spoke on why opening and closing the album with these two songs was so important, \"This album is more for my fans than anything else, who have stuck with me through times where I couldn\u2019t see a light at the end of the tunnel, or I thought, Who am I if I'm not doing this? They really gave me the strength to continue and to stay in a positive mind space. So book-ending [the album] with those two records is to give them some background and some insight. If I had ignored what I'd been through, it would have been a little odd.\"<ref name=\"thefader1\" /> In promotion for JoJo's [[III. (JoJo EP)|Tringle]], she embarked on the  \"[[I Am JoJo Tour]]\" at the end of 2015. Subsequently, during the tours run, JoJo's father Joel had passed away in November 2015 due to struggles with addiction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com.au/entry/jojo-dad-dead-at-60_n_5647a247e4b08cda34891cdf?ri18n=true |title=JoJo's Father, Joel Maurice Levesque, Dead At 60 &#124; HuffPost Australia |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com.au |date=2015-11-15 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>https://people.com/music/jojo-why-i-vote-video-dads-addiction-broke-family/</ref> Following the tour's conclusion in December 2015, JoJo was unhappy with the shape of the album and began re-writing and re-recording the entire album from scratch at the beginning of 2016.\n\n== Development ==\n\"Music.\" became the last song written during the whole album process.<ref name=\"iheart1\" /> JoJo recorded the song in only two takes to maintain the emotion she delivered in the song, \"the first time I literally choked; the second time I tried to get through it. I don't sound my best when I'm trying to sing through tears, so that\u2019s why I sound frog-ish at the end\".<ref name=\"thefader1\" /> Lyrically the song talks about how music has impacted and shaped JoJo's life, her upbringing and childhood, her relationship with her parents \"It's just a very personal song and I felt like we covered a lot of ground with the subject matter on 'Mad Love.,' but it was important that I touched on family and music almost feeling like my third parent\".<ref name=\"iheart1\" /><ref name=\"rap-up2\" /> Touching on her father's passing she states \"For as long as I had known my dad, he had been struggling with his addiction. It was never alcohol \u2014 always prescription drugs, but then it became whatever he could get. When I got the call [to say he had died] it was something I had kind of gone through many times before. Like, How is it going to feel when it happens? But I never knew how it was going to feel, of course, until it actually happened. It wasn\u2019t a total shock. I don't know if that makes it easier or harder. Was I supposed to cancel the [Tringle] tour, to honor him? I felt as though he wouldn\u2019t have wanted me to stop, because I\u2019ve been waiting for this moment. So I finished the tour.<ref name=\"thefader1\" />\n\n== Composition ==\n\"Music.\" was written by [[Hayley Warner]], Jussi Karvinen, [[Justin Tranter]] and [[JoJo (singer)|Joanna \"JoJo\" Levesque]] for the latter's long-awaited third studio album ''[[Mad Love (JoJo album)|Mad Love.]]'' (2016).<ref name=\"Notes\" /> It was produced by Jussifer, while the track was [[Sound recording and reproduction|recorded]] with guidance by Ryan Gladieux at [[Westlake Studios]] in [[Los Angeles, California]].<ref name=\"Notes\" /> The mixing of \"Music.\" was done by [[Adam Hawkins]] at Acacia Sound in Los Angeles, California and eventually, the [[audio mastering|mastering]] was done by [[Tom Coyne (music engineer)|Tom Coyne]] at Sterling Sound in New York. JoJo served as the songs vocal producer.<ref name=\"Notes\" />\n\n=== Critical reception ===\n\"Music.\" received majority of positive reviews from contemporary music critics, many praising the songs emotional weight and JoJo's raw vocal performance. Jon Reyes from \"[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]\" said it the best way to open up an album after ten years, \"with her huge voice paired exclusively with a piano. It\u2019s an earnest love letter to music itself\". Reyes went on to praise JoJo for not \"over-singing\" the song as easily as she could of much like her contemporaries counterparts that \"plague others blessed with pipes like hers\". in closing stating \"JoJo serenely offers up the words, and a little bit of herself: 'Went on the road to make my daddy proud / But I lost him and then I sang to the crowd / My only hope is that he\u2019s looking down thinking / \u2018Oh my God, my daughter\u2019s doing it now.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Jon Reyes |url=https://www.idolator.com/7648319/jojo-mad-love-review?firefox=1 |title=JoJo's 'Mad Love': Album Review |publisher=Idolator.com |date=2016-10-14 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> In writing for \"[[Time (magazine)|Time magazine]]\", Raisa Bruner praised the songs lyrical content describing it as \"both heartbreaking and uplifting\" and calling it \"a spare, deeply felt love song to the consistent power of music\".<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">https://time.com/4522855/watch-jojo-become-a-star-before-your-eyes-in-her-new-music-video/</ref> Meredith Jenks of \"[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]\" called the song a \"raw piano-ballad opener\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Billboard |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7486978/jojo-mad-love-interview-new-label |title=JoJo Gets Candid About Finally Breaking Free After Years of Label Limbo, Losing Her Father & Dealing With a Cheater |publisher=Billboard |date=2016-08-25 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> In an negative album review for Mad Love. Lillian Andemicael from \"[[The Diamondback]]\" highlighted \"Music\" as one of the only standout tracks from the album, \"an ode to JoJo\u2019s love for song and her late father, elicited such high hopes for the rest of the record. But after I continued listening to the release, it was clear that the opening song only set the bar for disappointment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dbknews.com/2016/10/18/review-jojo-mad-love-album/ |title=Review: \u2018Mad Love\u2019 fails to re-establish JoJo\u2019s relevancy \u2013 The Diamondback |publisher=Dbknews.com |date=2016-10-17 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nIn a slightly more positive review for the album Vanessa Okoth-Obbo from \"[[Pitchfork (magazine)|Pitchfork]]\" said it was \"encouraging to see that after all this time\" the risks JoJo took with the album paid off as sung in the song, \"every night I bet my life on you\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Vanessa Okoth-Obbo |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/22545-mad-love/ |title=JoJo: Mad Love. Album Review |publisher=Pitchfork |date=2016-10-27 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> In a summary for [[Apple Music]] the sing was described as a \"powerful meditation on her late father\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/mad-love-deluxe/1153048003 |title=Mad Love. (Deluxe) by JoJo on Apple Music |publisher=Music.apple.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> In writing for \"[[The Guardian]]\"s\u2019 [[The Observer]] Michael Cragg described the song as a \"trampled under the emotional weight\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Michael Cragg |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/oct/16/jojo-mad-love-review |title=JoJo: Mad Love review \u2013 no match for her mixtapes &#124; Music |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> Andy Kellman from \"[[AllMusic]]\" called the song a \"soul-baring ballad\".<ref>{{cite web|author=AllMusic Review by Andy Kellman |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/mad-love-mw0002979928 |title=Mad Love \u2013 JoJo &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits |publisher=AllMusic |date=2016-10-14 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> Chelsea Stone from \"[[Teen Vogue]]\" called the song a \"total emotional throwback to JoJo's own childhood\", while in closing describing the songs climax as \"especially heart-wrenching\" when JoJo sings about her fathers passing.<ref name=\"teenvogue1\">{{cite web|last=Stone |first=Chelsea |url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/jojo-release-music-video-single-emotional-journey |title=Watch JoJo\u2019s New Video for Her Single \u201cMusic\u201d |publisher=Teen Vogue |date=2016-10-07 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> In a review from [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]], \"Music\" was described as \"emotionally gut-punching\" while the songs lyrical content was described as \"heart-tugging\".<ref name=\"billboard1\">{{cite web|author=Billboard |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7534159/jojo-shares-childhood-home-videos-in-touching-video-for-music-watch |title=JoJo Shares Her Childhood Home Videos in Touching 'Music' Video: Watch |publisher=Billboard |date=2016-10-07 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> [[Rap-Up (magazine)|Rap-Up]] magazine stated that JoJo \"tugs at heart strings\" and called the song a \"tear-jerking trip down memory lane\" with \"soaring vocals\".<ref name=\"rap-up1\" />\n\n== Music video ==\nOn July 28, 2016, JoJo officially announced the release of her third studio album ''[[Mad Love (JoJo album)|Mad Love.]]'' (2016) in a short promotional video which included a snippet of the song and the songs video.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6MFtj3cynPM |title=Mad Love. 10.14.16 |publisher=YouTube |date=2016-07-27 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\"Music.\" made its official premiere on October 7, 2016 as the third and final promotional single from the album, alongside the songs music video.<ref name=\"rap-up1\" /> The music video is a [[VHS]] themed compilation that consists of old home movies and videos from JoJo's childhood, showing her performing on stage from a young age, dancing, acting, doing interviews and recording her first demo in studio as a toddler, as she sings about working for years to achieve her dream of being a singer.<ref name=\"rap-up1\" /><ref name=\"teenvogue1\" /><ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> Clips of JoJo's father are shown while she was a guest on [[Kids Say the Darnedest Things]], proudly watching from the audience as JoJo performs.<ref name=\"teenvogue1\" /> [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] magazine said the music video is and endless tape of \"before she was famous footage\", calling it a \"nostalgic waltz through her memories\".<ref name=\"billboard1\" />\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{track listing\n| total_length    = 3:35\n| extra_column    = Producer(s)\n| headline        = Digital download <ref name=\"Music Single\">{{cite web|title=Music. - Single by JoJo<!--|title=Music. - Single by JoJo -->|url=https://tidal.com/browse/album/65489950|website=[[Tidal (service)|TIDAL]] (US)|publisher=[[Aspiro]]|accessdate=7 October 2016}}</ref>\n| title1 = Music.\n| writer1 = {{Flatlist|\n* [[JoJo (singer)|Joanna Levesque]]\n* Jussi Karvinen\n* [[Justin Tranter]]\n* [[Hayley Warner]]\n}}\n| extra1 = Jussifer\n| length1 = 3:35\n}}\n\n== Credits and personnel ==\nCredits adapted from the liner notes of ''[[Mad Love (JoJo album)|Mad Love.]]'', [[Atlantic Records]].<ref name=\"Notes\">{{cite AV media notes|others=JoJo|title=[[Mad Love. (JoJo album)|Mad Love.]]|year=2016|type= inlay cover |publisher=[[Atlantic Records]]}}</ref>\n\n;Recording\n*Recorded at [[Westlake Studios]], [[Los Angeles, California]]\n*Mixed at Acacia Sound, Los Angeles, California\n*Mastered at [[Sterling Sound]], New York, NY\n;Personnel\n{{Div col}}\n*[[JoJo (singer)|JoJo]] \u2013 [[Vocal music|vocals]], [[writing]], vocal production\n*Jussi Karvinen \u2013 writing\n*[[Hayley Warner]] \u2013 writing\n*[[Justin Tranter]] \u2013 writing\n*[[Adam Hawkins]] \u2013 [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mixing]]\n*Ryan Gladieux \u2013 [[Sound recording and reproduction|recording]]\n*Jussifer \u2013 [[Record producer|producer]]\n*[[Tom Coyne (music engineer)|Tom Coyne]] \u2013 [[audio mastering]]\n*Evan Lipschutz \u2013 [[A&R]]\n*Anne Declemente \u2013 A&R administration\n*Gita Willams \u2013 [[management]]\n*Katie Gallagher \u2013 management\n*Chris Smith \u2013 management\n{{Div col end}}\n\n== Release history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Region\n! scope=\"col\"| Date\n! scope=\"col\"| Format\n! scope=\"col\"| Label\n! scope=\"col\"| {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Various\n| October 7, 2016\n| {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n|| [[Atlantic Records]]\n| <ref name=\"Music Single\" />\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{JoJo}}\n\n[[Category:2016 singles]]\n[[Category:2016 songs]]\n[[Category:JoJo (singer) songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Justin Tranter]]\n[[Category:Songs written by JoJo (singer)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Hayley Warner]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Music.\n| cover      = \n| alt        =\n| type       = [[Promotional single]]\n| artist     = [[JoJo (singer)|JoJo]]\n| album      = [[Mad Love (JoJo album)|Mad Love.]]\n| B-side     = \n| released   = {{Start date|2016|10|07}}\n| format     =\n* [[Music download|Digital download]]\n* [[Streaming media|Streaming]]\n| recorded   = 2016\n| studio     = [[Westlake Studios]]\n| genre      =\n* [[Pop music|Pop]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n| length     = 3:35\n| label      = \n*[[Atlantic Records]]\n| writer      =\n* [[JoJo (singer)|Joanna Levesque]]\n*Jussi Karvinen\n*[[Hayley Warner]]\n*[[Justin Tranter]]\n| producer   =\n* Jussifer\n| misc     = {{External music video|{{YouTube|0m4xsDviZQM|\"Music.\"}}|type=song}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Music.'''\"  is a song by American [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] singer-songwriter [[JoJo (singer)|JoJo]] from her third studio album ''[[Mad Love (JoJo album)|Mad Love.]]'' (2016). It was written by [[JoJo (singer)|Joanna Levesque]], Jussi Karvinen, [[Hayley Warner]] and [[Justin Tranter]], while the songs production was helmed by Jussifer. The song was released as the third and final promotional single from the album on October 7, 2016.<ref name=\"rap-up1\">https://www.rap-up.com/2016/10/06/video-jojo-music/</ref> Sonically, \"Music.\" is a piano driven [[pop ballad]] with [[contemporary R&B|R&B]] influences. Lyrically, the song is a vivid storytelling of JoJo's upbringing, growth, her love for music and family, including and ode to JoJo's father Joel Levesque who passed away in November 2015, while JoJo was in early recording sessions for the album.<ref name=\"rap-up2\">https://www.rap-up.com/rap-up-tv/jojo-talks-mad-love-kehlani-chance-the-rapper/</ref>\n\nThe song received generally positive reviews from contemporary music critics, with many praising the songs emotional weight and JoJo's raw vocal performance. JoJo dedicated the song to her father and links to the subject matter spoken about in her song \"Save my Soul\" from her \"''[[III (JoJo EP)|Tringle]]''\" (2015) EP. The song's accompanying music video premiered on JoJo's official [[YouTube]] channel on October 7, 2016, it consisted of clips of JoJo performing on stage, recording in studio, and doing interviews as a toddler as well as footage of her parents in a [[VHS]] style video. In promotion for her third album, \"Music.\" was included in the set list for JoJo's [[Mad Love Tour|Mad Love World Tour]].\n\n== Background ==\nThe song was originally titled \"Who Would I Be\" during the writing and recording process, JoJo opted to change the title to \"Music\" as the overall subject of the song related to music being her first love.<ref name=\"BMI Credits\">Title\u2013 ''Music''. [[Broadcast Music, Inc.]] BMI Work Number: 21885299.</ref> During the recording process for ''[[Mad Love (JoJo album)|Mad Love.]]'' (2016), \"Music.\" was the \"most personal\" and \"most difficult\" song to write and record for JoJo while serving as the opening song in the albums sequence.<ref name=\"iheart1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.iheart.com/content/2016-10-14-jojo-on-new-album-mad-love-details-alessia-cara-remy-ma-collabs/ |title=INTERVIEW: JoJo On New Album 'Mad Love.' &#124; iHeartRadio |publisher=Iheart.com |date=2016-10-14 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref name=\"rap-up2\" /> The song has been described as \"autobiographical\" and \"soul-searching\" along with \"I Am\", a song that closes up the standard edition of ''Mad Love''.<ref name=\"thefader1\">{{cite web|last=Myers |first=Owen |url=https://www.thefader.com/2016/10/12/jojo-interview-mad-love |title=How JoJo Found Her Voice, Again |publisher=The Fader |date=2016-10-12 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> In an interview with TheFader, JoJo spoke on why opening and closing the album with these two songs was so important, \"This album is more for my fans than anything else, who have stuck with me through times where I couldn\u2019t see a light at the end of the tunnel, or I thought, Who am I if I'm not doing this? They really gave me the strength to continue and to stay in a positive mind space. So book-ending [the album] with those two records is to give them some background and some insight. If I had ignored what I'd been through, it would have been a little odd.\"<ref name=\"thefader1\" /> In promotion for JoJo's [[III. (JoJo EP)|Tringle]], she embarked on the  \"[[I Am JoJo Tour]]\" at the end of 2015. Subsequently, during the tours run, JoJo's father Joel had passed away in November 2015 due to struggles with addiction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com.au/entry/jojo-dad-dead-at-60_n_5647a247e4b08cda34891cdf?ri18n=true |title=JoJo's Father, Joel Maurice Levesque, Dead At 60 &#124; HuffPost Australia |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com.au |date=2015-11-15 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>https://people.com/music/jojo-why-i-vote-video-dads-addiction-broke-family/</ref> Following the tour's conclusion in December 2015, JoJo was unhappy with the shape of the album and began re-writing and re-recording the entire album from scratch at the beginning of 2016.\n\n== Development ==\n\"Music.\" became the last song written during the whole album process.<ref name=\"iheart1\" /> JoJo recorded the song in only two takes to maintain the emotion she delivered in the song, \"the first time I literally choked; the second time I tried to get through it. I don't sound my best when I'm trying to sing through tears, so that\u2019s why I sound frog-ish at the end\".<ref name=\"thefader1\" /> Lyrically the song talks about how music has impacted and shaped JoJo's life, her upbringing and childhood, her relationship with her parents \"It's just a very personal song and I felt like we covered a lot of ground with the subject matter on 'Mad Love.,' but it was important that I touched on family and music almost feeling like my third parent\".<ref name=\"iheart1\" /><ref name=\"rap-up2\" /> Touching on her father's passing she states \"For as long as I had known my dad, he had been struggling with his addiction. It was never alcohol \u2014 always prescription drugs, but then it became whatever he could get. When I got the call [to say he had died] it was something I had kind of gone through many times before. Like, How is it going to feel when it happens? But I never knew how it was going to feel, of course, until it actually happened. It wasn\u2019t a total shock. I don't know if that makes it easier or harder. Was I supposed to cancel the [Tringle] tour, to honor him? I felt as though he wouldn\u2019t have wanted me to stop, because I\u2019ve been waiting for this moment. So I finished the tour.<ref name=\"thefader1\" />\n\n== Composition ==\n\"Music.\" was written by [[Hayley Warner]], Jussi Karvinen, [[Justin Tranter]] and [[JoJo (singer)|Joanna \"JoJo\" Levesque]] for the latter's long-awaited third studio album ''[[Mad Love (JoJo album)|Mad Love.]]'' (2016).<ref name=\"Notes\" /> It was produced by Jussifer, while the track was [[Sound recording and reproduction|recorded]] with guidance by Ryan Gladieux at [[Westlake Studios]] in [[Los Angeles, California]].<ref name=\"Notes\" /> The mixing of \"Music.\" was done by [[Adam Hawkins]] at Acacia Sound in Los Angeles, California and eventually, the [[audio mastering|mastering]] was done by [[Tom Coyne (music engineer)|Tom Coyne]] at Sterling Sound in New York. JoJo served as the songs vocal producer.<ref name=\"Notes\" />\n\n=== Critical reception ===\n\"Music.\" received majority of positive reviews from contemporary music critics, many praising the songs emotional weight and JoJo's raw vocal performance. Jon Reyes from \"[[Idolator]]\" said it the best way to open up an album after ten years, \"with her huge voice paired exclusively with a piano. It\u2019s an earnest love letter to music itself\". Reyes went on to praise JoJo for not \"over-singing\" the song as easily as she could of much like her contemporaries counterparts that \"plague others blessed with pipes like hers\". in closing stating \"JoJo serenely offers up the words, and a little bit of herself: 'Went on the road to make my daddy proud / But I lost him and then I sang to the crowd / My only hope is that he\u2019s looking down thinking / \u2018Oh my God, my daughter\u2019s doing it now.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Jon Reyes |url=https://www.idolator.com/7648319/jojo-mad-love-review?firefox=1 |title=JoJo's 'Mad Love': Album Review |publisher=Idolator.com |date=2016-10-14 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> In writing for \"[[Time (magazine)|Time magazine]]\", Raisa Bruner praised the songs lyrical content describing it as \"both heartbreaking and uplifting\" and calling it \"a spare, deeply felt love song to the consistent power of music\".<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">https://time.com/4522855/watch-jojo-become-a-star-before-your-eyes-in-her-new-music-video/</ref> Meredith Jenks of \"[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]\" called the song a \"raw piano-ballad opener\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Billboard |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7486978/jojo-mad-love-interview-new-label |title=JoJo Gets Candid About Finally Breaking Free After Years of Label Limbo, Losing Her Father & Dealing With a Cheater |publisher=Billboard |date=2016-08-25 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> In an negative album review for Mad Love. Lillian Andemicael from \"[[The Diamondback]]\" highlighted \"Music\" as one of the only standout tracks from the album, \"an ode to JoJo\u2019s love for song and her late father, elicited such high hopes for the rest of the record. But after I continued listening to the release, it was clear that the opening song only set the bar for disappointment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dbknews.com/2016/10/18/review-jojo-mad-love-album/ |title=Review: \u2018Mad Love\u2019 fails to re-establish JoJo\u2019s relevancy \u2013 The Diamondback |publisher=Dbknews.com |date=2016-10-17 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nIn a slightly more positive review for the album Vanessa Okoth-Obbo from \"[[Pitchfork (magazine)|Pitchfork]]\" said it was \"encouraging to see that after all this time\" the risks JoJo took with the album paid off as sung in the song, \"every night I bet my life on you\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Vanessa Okoth-Obbo |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/22545-mad-love/ |title=JoJo: Mad Love. Album Review |publisher=Pitchfork |date=2016-10-27 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> In a summary for [[Apple Music]] the sing was described as a \"powerful meditation on her late father\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/mad-love-deluxe/1153048003 |title=Mad Love. (Deluxe) by JoJo on Apple Music |publisher=Music.apple.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> In writing for \"[[The Guardian]]\"s\u2019 [[The Observer]] Michael Cragg described the song as a \"trampled under the emotional weight\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Michael Cragg |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/oct/16/jojo-mad-love-review |title=JoJo: Mad Love review \u2013 no match for her mixtapes &#124; Music |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> Andy Kellman from \"[[AllMusic]]\" called the song a \"soul-baring ballad\".<ref>{{cite web|author=AllMusic Review by Andy Kellman |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/mad-love-mw0002979928 |title=Mad Love \u2013 JoJo &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits |publisher=AllMusic |date=2016-10-14 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> Chelsea Stone from \"[[Teen Vogue]]\" called the song a \"total emotional throwback to JoJo's own childhood\", while in closing describing the songs climax as \"especially heart-wrenching\" when JoJo sings about her fathers passing.<ref name=\"teenvogue1\">{{cite web|last=Stone |first=Chelsea |url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/jojo-release-music-video-single-emotional-journey |title=Watch JoJo\u2019s New Video for Her Single \u201cMusic\u201d |publisher=Teen Vogue |date=2016-10-07 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> In a review from [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]], \"Music\" was described as \"emotionally gut-punching\" while the songs lyrical content was described as \"heart-tugging\".<ref name=\"billboard1\">{{cite web|author=Billboard |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7534159/jojo-shares-childhood-home-videos-in-touching-video-for-music-watch |title=JoJo Shares Her Childhood Home Videos in Touching 'Music' Video: Watch |publisher=Billboard |date=2016-10-07 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> [[Rap-Up (magazine)|Rap-Up]] magazine stated that JoJo \"tugs at heart strings\" and called the song a \"tear-jerking trip down memory lane\" with \"soaring vocals\".<ref name=\"rap-up1\" />\n\n== Music video ==\nOn July 28, 2016, JoJo officially announced the release of her third studio album ''[[Mad Love (JoJo album)|Mad Love.]]'' (2016) in a short promotional video which included a snippet of the song and the songs video.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6MFtj3cynPM |title=Mad Love. 10.14.16 |publisher=YouTube |date=2016-07-27 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\"Music.\" made its official premiere on October 7, 2016 as the third and final promotional single from the album, alongside the songs music video.<ref name=\"rap-up1\" /> The music video is a [[VHS]] themed compilation that consists of old home movies and videos from JoJo's childhood, showing her performing on stage from a young age, dancing, acting, doing interviews and recording her first demo in studio as a toddler, as she sings about working for years to achieve her dream of being a singer.<ref name=\"rap-up1\" /><ref name=\"teenvogue1\" /><ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> Clips of JoJo's father are shown while she was a guest on [[Kids Say the Darnedest Things]], proudly watching from the audience as JoJo performs.<ref name=\"teenvogue1\" /> [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] magazine said the music video is and endless tape of \"before she was famous footage\", calling it a \"nostalgic waltz through her memories\".<ref name=\"billboard1\" />\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{track listing\n| total_length    = 3:35\n| extra_column    = Producer(s)\n| headline        = Digital download <ref name=\"Music Single\">{{cite web|title=Music. - Single by JoJo<!--|title=Music. - Single by JoJo -->|url=https://tidal.com/browse/album/65489950|website=[[Tidal (service)|TIDAL]] (US)|publisher=[[Aspiro]]|accessdate=7 October 2016}}</ref>\n| title1 = Music.\n| writer1 = {{Flatlist|\n* [[JoJo (singer)|Joanna Levesque]]\n* Jussi Karvinen\n* [[Justin Tranter]]\n* [[Hayley Warner]]\n}}\n| extra1 = Jussifer\n| length1 = 3:35\n}}\n\n== Credits and personnel ==\nCredits adapted from the liner notes of ''[[Mad Love (JoJo album)|Mad Love.]]'', [[Atlantic Records]].<ref name=\"Notes\">{{cite AV media notes|others=JoJo|title=[[Mad Love. (JoJo album)|Mad Love.]]|year=2016|type= inlay cover |publisher=[[Atlantic Records]]}}</ref>\n\n;Recording\n*Recorded at [[Westlake Studios]], [[Los Angeles, California]]\n*Mixed at Acacia Sound, Los Angeles, California\n*Mastered at [[Sterling Sound]], New York, NY\n;Personnel\n{{Div col}}\n*[[JoJo (singer)|JoJo]] \u2013 [[Vocal music|vocals]], [[writing]], vocal production\n*Jussi Karvinen \u2013 writing\n*[[Hayley Warner]] \u2013 writing\n*[[Justin Tranter]] \u2013 writing\n*[[Adam Hawkins]] \u2013 [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mixing]]\n*Ryan Gladieux \u2013 [[Sound recording and reproduction|recording]]\n*Jussifer \u2013 [[Record producer|producer]]\n*[[Tom Coyne (music engineer)|Tom Coyne]] \u2013 [[audio mastering]]\n*Evan Lipschutz \u2013 [[A&R]]\n*Anne Declemente \u2013 A&R administration\n*Gita Willams \u2013 [[management]]\n*Katie Gallagher \u2013 management\n*Chris Smith \u2013 management\n{{Div col end}}\n\n== Release history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Region\n! scope=\"col\"| Date\n! scope=\"col\"| Format\n! scope=\"col\"| Label\n! scope=\"col\"| {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Various\n| October 7, 2016\n| {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n|| [[Atlantic Records]]\n| <ref name=\"Music Single\" />\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{JoJo}}\n\n[[Category:2016 singles]]\n[[Category:2016 songs]]\n[[Category:JoJo (singer) songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Justin Tranter]]\n[[Category:Songs written by JoJo (singer)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Hayley Warner]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records singles]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toIdolator(link changed toIdolator (website)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Music_(JoJo_song)"}
{"title_page": "Jeffrey Moussaieff Masson", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer  <!--For more information, see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]].-->\n| name = Jeffrey Moussaieff Masson\n| honorific_prefix = \n| honorific_suffix = \n| image = Jeffrey_Moussaieff_Masson.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Appearing on the UK TV programme ''[[After Dark (TV series)|After Dark]]'' in 1989\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| pseudonym = \n| birth_name = Jeffrey Lloyd Masson\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1941|03|28}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date =    <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place = \n| resting_place = \n| occupation = \n| language = \n| nationality = American\n| ethnicity = \n| citizenship = \n| education = \n| alma_mater = [[Harvard University]]\n| period = \n| genre =\n| subject = [[Psychoanalysis]]\n| movement = \n| notablework = ''[[The Assault on Truth]]'' (1984)\n| spouse =        <!-- or: | spouses =     -->\n| partner =       <!-- or: | partners =    -->\n| children = \n| relatives = \n| awards = \n| signature = \n| signature_alt = \n| years_active = \n| module = \n| website = \n| portaldisp =    <!-- \"on\", \"yes\", \"true\", etc; or omit -->\n}}\n'''Jeffrey Moussaieff Masson''' (born March 28, 1941 as '''Jeffrey Lloyd Masson''') is an American author. Masson is best known for his conclusions about [[Sigmund Freud]] and [[psychoanalysis]]. In his ''[[The Assault on Truth]]'' (1984), Masson argues that Freud may have abandoned his [[Freud's seduction theory|seduction theory]] because he feared that granting the truth of his female patients' claims (that they had been [[sexual abuse|sexually abused]]) would hinder the acceptance of his [[psychoanalysis|psychoanalytic]] methods. Masson is a [[veganism]] advocate and has written about [[animal rights]].<ref name=Jeff>{{cite web|url=http://www.jeffreymasson.com/about.html |title=About Jeff |publisher=Jeffreymasson.com |date= |accessdate=2012-01-05}}</ref>\n\n== Life and career ==\nJeffrey Masson is the son of Jacques Masson, a Frenchman of [[Bukharian Jew|Bukharian]] ancestry, and Diana (Dina) Zeiger from an [[Ashkenazi]] strict [[Orthodox Jew]]ish family. Both of his parents were followers of the [[guru]] [[Paul Brunton]].<ref name=\"NY\"/> Masson's mother later became a follower of [[Mysticism|mystic]] [[John Levy (philosopher)|John Levy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ods.nl/am1gos/am1gos5/index.html?jl_vriend_us.html~mainFrame |title=John Levy: friend and contrary guru |publisher=Ods.nl |date= |accessdate=2012-01-05}}</ref> During the 1940s and 1950s, Brunton often lived with them, eventually designating Masson as his [[heir apparent]]. In 1956, Diana and Jacques Masson moved to [[Uruguay]] because Brunton believed that a [[World War III|third world war]] was imminent. Jeffrey and his sister Linda followed in 1959.\n\nAt Brunton's urging, Masson went to [[Harvard University]] to study [[Sanskrit]]. While at Harvard, Masson became disillusioned with Brunton. Brunton and his influence on the Masson family form the subject of Masson's autobiographical book ''My Father's Guru: A Journey Through Spirituality and Disillusion''. [[Harvard University]] granted Masson a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in 1964 and a [[Ph.D.]] with Honors in 1970. His degrees were in [[Sanskrit]] and [[Indian Studies]]. While undertaking his Ph.D., Masson also studied, supported by fellowships, at the [[\u00c9cole Normale Sup\u00e9rieure]] in Paris, the [[University of Calcutta]], and the [[University of Poona]].\n\nMasson taught Sanskrit and Indian Studies at the [[University of Toronto]], 1969\u201380, reaching the rank of Professor. He has also held short term appointments at [[Brown University]], the [[University of California]], and the [[University of Michigan]]. From 1981 to 1992, he was a Research Associate, Department of South and Southeast Asian Studies, at the [[University of California, Berkeley]]. He is currently an Honorary Fellow in the Department of [[Philosophy]] at the [[University of Auckland]] in New Zealand.\n\n== Views on Freud's seduction theory ==\nIn 1970, Masson began studying to become a psychoanalyst at the Toronto Psychoanalytic Institute, completing a full clinical training course in 1978. His training analyst was Irvine Schiffer, a well-known Toronto analyst and author of books on the unconscious aspects of charisma and time. In 1990 Masson published an autobiographical book in which he accused Schiffer of cursing, being constantly late for sessions, and intimidating Masson when the latter complained about this issue.<ref name=\"Final Analysis\">{{cite book |last=Masson |first=Jeffrey |year=1990 |title=Final Analysis: The Making and Unmaking of a Psychoanalyst |publisher=Addison-Wesley |isbn=0-201-52368-X}}</ref> Schiffer denied it and debated Masson on the Canadian television program ''[[The Fifth Estate (TV)|The Fifth Estate]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=61MAAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA40 | title=Love is Strange | publisher=([[Google Books]]) | work=[[New York Magazine]] | date=March 22, 1993 | accessdate=November 14, 2012 | author=Smith, Dinitia}}</ref>\n\nDuring this time, Masson befriended the psychoanalyst [[Kurt Eissler]] and became acquainted with [[Sigmund Freud]]'s daughter [[Anna Freud]]. Eissler designated Masson to succeed him as Director of the [[Sigmund Freud Archives]] after his and Anna Freud's death. Masson learned [[German language|German]] and studied the [[history of psychoanalysis]]. In 1980 Masson was appointed Projects Director of the Freud Archives, with full access to Freud's correspondence and other unpublished papers. While perusing this material, Masson concluded that Freud might have rejected the seduction theory in order to advance the cause of [[psychoanalysis]] and to maintain his own place within the psychoanalytic inner circle, after a hostile response from the renowned sex-pathologist [[Richard von Krafft-Ebing]] and the rest of the Vienna Psychiatric Society in 1896 - \"an icy reception from the jackasses,\" was the way Freud described it later to Fliess\n<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?sec=health&res=9A0CEFDA123BF936A1575BC0A967948260 \"Did Freud's Isolation Lead Him to Reverse Theory on Neurosis?\"] by Ralph Blumenthal, ''[[New York Times]]'', August 25, 1981</ref>\n\nIn 1981, Masson's controversial conclusions were discussed in a series of ''[[New York Times]]'' articles by Ralph Blumenthal, to the dismay of the psychoanalytic establishment. Masson was subsequently dismissed from his position as project director of the Freud Archives and stripped of his membership in psychoanalytic professional societies. Masson was defended by [[Alice Miller (psychologist)|Alice Miller]]<ref>PSYCHOLOGIE HEUTE, April 1987, P.21, 22: \"Im Gegensatz zu manchen Interpreten, die, wie zum Beispiel Marianne Kr\u00fcll, Marie Balmary oder Jeffrey Masson, Freuds Abkehr von der Wahrheit als Folge seiner Familiengeschichte deuten, sehe ich diesen Schritt als Folge und Ausdruck unserer jahrtausendealten kinderfeindlichen Tradition, in der wir auch heute noch leben. Die Ergebnisse der oben genannten historischen Forscher k\u00f6nnen trotzdem korrekt sein, aber ich meine, da\u00df es Freud trotz der pers\u00f6nlichen Familiengeschichte m\u00f6glich gewesen w\u00e4re, seiner Entdeckung treu zu bleiben, wenn die Gesellschaft als Ganzes nicht so kinderfeindlich gewesen w\u00e4re, wenn schon damals andere, freiere Erziehungsmuster denkbar gewesen w\u00e4ren. Doch zur Zeit Freuds war es noch absolut unm\u00f6glich, die Unschuld der Eltern in Frage zu stellen.\" Alice Miller in interview entitled ''Wie Psychotherapien das Kind verraten''</ref>\nand [[Muriel Gardiner]] (\"While striving not to take sides,\" Gardiner said, \"I consider him a good and energetic worker and a worthwhile scholar\").<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?sec=health&res=9400E3DA1E39F93AA35752C1A967948260 \"Freud Archives Research Chief Removed in Dispute Over Yale Talk\"] by Ralph Blumenthal, ''[[New York Times]]'' November 9, 1981.</ref>\n\nMasson later wrote several books critical of psychoanalysis, including ''The Assault on Truth: Freud's Suppression of the Seduction Theory''. In the introduction to ''The Assault on Truth'', Masson challenged his critics to address his arguments: \"My pessimistic conclusions may possibly be wrong. The documents may in fact allow a very different reading.\"<ref>{{cite book |first=Jeffrey |last=Masson |year=1992 |title=The Assault on Truth: Freud's Suppression of the Seduction Theory |publisher=Harper Perennial |location=New York |isbn= 0-06-097457-5 |pages= xxxv |nopp=true}}</ref> [[Janet Malcolm]] interviewed Masson at length when writing her long ''[[The New Yorker|New Yorker]]'' article on this controversy, which she later expanded into ''[[In the Freud Archives]]'', a book that also dealt with Eissler and [[Peter Swales (historian)|Peter Swales]]. Masson sued ''The New Yorker'' for [[defamation]], claiming that Malcolm had misquoted him. The ensuing trial drew considerable attention.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Psychoanalyst Loses Libel Suit Against a New Yorker Reporter | work = [[The New York Times]] | date = 1994-11-03 | author = David Margolick}}</ref> The decade-long, [[US$]]10 million lawsuit came to a close in 1994 when the court ruled in ''The New Yorker'' 's favor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/books/the-journalist-and-the-biographer/2007/10/04/1191091267930.html?page=fullpage#contentSwap2 |title=SMH article October 6, 2007 |publisher=Smh.com.au |date=2007-10-06 |accessdate=2012-01-05}}</ref> \"The Court of Appeals affirmed ... that Malcolm had deliberately altered each quotation not found on the tape recordings, but nevertheless held that petitioner failed to raise a jury question of actual malice.\"<ref>{{Cite web|title=Masson v. New Yorker Magazine, Inc. (89-1799), 501 U.S. 496 (1991)|url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/supct/html/89-1799.ZO.html|work=Masson v. New Yorker Magazine, Inc. (89-1799), 501 U.S. 496 (1991)|publisher=Supreme Court/Cornell University Law School|year=1991|accessdate=Oct 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985, Masson edited and translated Freud's complete correspondence with [[Wilhelm Fliess]] after having convinced Anna Freud to make it available in full. He also looked up the original places and documents in La [[Salp\u00eatri\u00e8re]] Hospital in Paris,<ref>[http://www.paris.org/Kiosque/sep98/la.salpetriere.html History of La Salp\u00eatri\u00e8re] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110103105500/http://www.paris.org/Kiosque/sep98/la.salpetriere.html |date=January 3, 2011 }}</ref> where Freud had studied with [[Jean-Martin Charcot|Charcot]]. Masson writes that the scientific community has been largely silent about his views, and that he suffered personal attacks once he deviated from the traditional views on the seduction theory and the history of psychoanalysis.<ref name=\"Final Analysis\"/> Both the traditional view and Masson's case against it are built on the account that Freud's seduction theory patients reported having been sexually abused in early childhood; several Freud scholars have disputed this account.<ref>Schimek, J. G. (1987). Fact and Fantasy in the Seduction Theory: a Historical Review. ''Journal of the American Psychoanalytic Association'', xxxv: 937-65; Isra\u00ebls, H. and Schatzman, M. (1993) The Seduction Theory. ''History of Psychiatry'', iv: 23-59; Esterson, A. (1998). [http://human-nature.com/esterson/synopsis.html Jeffrey Masson and Freud\u2019s seduction theory: a new fable based on old myths]. ''History of the Human Sciences'', 11 (1), pp. 1-21; Esterson, A. (2001). The mythologizing of psychoanalytic history: deception and self deception in Freud's accounts of the seduction theory episode. ''History of Psychiatry'', Vol. 12 (3), pp. 329-352; Eissler, K. R. (2001) ''Freud and the Seduction Theory: A Brief Love Affair.'' International Universities Press, pp. 107-117.</ref>\n\n== Recent work ==\nSince the early 1990s, Masson has written a number of books on the emotional life of animals, one of which, ''When Elephants Weep'', has been translated into 20 languages. He has explained this radical change in the subject of his writings as follows:\n\n{{quote|I'd written a whole series of books about [[psychiatry]], and nobody bought them. Nobody liked them. Nobody. Psychiatrists hated them, and they were much too abstruse for the general public. It was very hard to make a living, and I thought, \"As long as I'm not making a living, I may as well write about something I really love: animals.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.powells.com/authors/masson.html |title=Interviews&nbsp;\u2014 Jeffrey Masson |publisher=Powells.com |date= |access-date=2012-01-05 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629103347/http://www.powells.com/authors/masson.html |archive-date=2011-06-29 |df= }}</ref>}}\n\nIn 2008, Masson became a Director of [[Voiceless, the animal protection institute]].  \"We are not encouraged, on a daily basis, to pay careful attention to the animals we eat. On the contrary, the meat, dairy, and egg industries all actively encourage us to give thought to our own immediate interest (taste, for example, or cheap food) but not to the real suffering involved ... The animals involved suffer agony because of our ignorance. The least we owe them is to lessen that ignorance\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Voiceless, the animal protection institute|url=https://www.voiceless.org.au/who-we-are/jeffrey-masson}}</ref>\n\nMasson also wrote a book about living in New Zealand, including an interview with Sir [[Edmund Hillary]].<ref>Masson, J., \"A Conversation with a Great Ordinary Kiwi: Sir Edmund Hillary,\" chpt. 7 in ''Slipping into Paradise''.</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nMasson is married to Leila Masson, a German [[pediatrics|pediatrician]].<ref name=\"NY\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leilamasson.com |title=Dr. Leila Masson |publisher=Leilamasson.com |date= |accessdate=2012-01-05}}</ref> They have two sons. He also has a daughter by a previous marriage with Therese Claire Masson.<ref name=Jeff/> In the early 1990s, Masson had been engaged to [[University of Michigan]] [[feminist]] legal scholar [[Catharine MacKinnon]], who wrote the preface to his ''A Dark Science: Women, Sexuality, and Psychiatry in the Nineteenth Century''.<ref>{{Cite news| volume = 26| issue = 12| pages = 36\u201343| last = Smith| first = Dinitia| title = Love is Strange: The Crusading Feminist and the Repentant Womanizer| work = [[New York Magazine|New York]]| accessdate = 2010-02-14| date = 1993-03-22| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=61MAAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA36&pg=PA36#v=onepage&q=&f=false}} ([https://books.google.com/books?id=61MAAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q=&f=false cover])</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2006/apr/12/gender.politicsphilosophyandsociety \"Are women human?\"] by Stuart Jeffries, ''[[The Guardian]]'', April 12, 2006.</ref>\n\nMasson became a [[veganism|vegan]] in 2004.<ref name=\"NY\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/15/dining/15mass.html?pagewanted=all |title=A Man With Opinions on Food With a Face |first=Eric |last=Konigsberg |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=14 April 2009 |accessdate=19 April 2012}}</ref> He is an [[animal rights]] activist.<ref name=Jeff/>\n\n== Name ==\nMasson's great-grandfather [[Shlomo Moussaieff (rabbi)|Shlomo Moussaieff]] was a [[Kabbalah|kabbalist]] and founder of the [[Bukharim|Bukharian Quarter]] in [[Jerusalem]]. His grandfather Henry Mousaieff changed his family name from Moussaieff to Masson. Masson changed his middle name from Lloyd to Moussaieff.<ref name=Moussaieff>Wagner, Frank D. (2004). [https://books.google.com/books?id=Jf-6mBUJHp0C&pg=PA504&lpg=PA504&dq=Jeffrey+Moussaieff+Masson+%22his+middle+name%22&source=bl&ots=7e52RezlBt&sig=ACfU3U3XHzemNwsnpq7nHnb3K38HHId6LA&hl=en&ppis=_e&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjVr63_8_XnAhVWhHIEHQevAkUQ6AEwB3oECBYQAQ#v=onepage&q=Jeffrey%20Moussaieff%20Masson%20%22his%20middle%20name%22&f=false ''United States Reports: Cases Adjudged in the Supreme Court'']. Washington, DC: U.S. Government Printing Office. p. 504. {{ISBN|0-16-048116-3}}.</ref>\n\n== Works ==\n* 1974. \"India and the Unconscious: Erik Erikson on Gandhi,\" ''[[International Journal of Psycho-Analysis]]'' 55: 519-26. Discussion by T. C. Sinha: 527.\n* 1974. \"Sex and Yoga: Psychoanalysis and the Indian Religious Experience\", ''[[Journal of Indian Philosophy]]'' 2: 307\u2013320. Reprinted in ''Vishnu on Freud's Desk: A Reader in Psychoanalysis and Hinduism'', T.G. Vaidyanathan and [[Jeffrey J. Kripal]] eds. [[Oxford University Press]], {{ISBN|0-19-565835-3}}, Paperback (Edition: 2003)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exoticindiaart.com/book/details/IDG634/ |title=Table of Contents |publisher=Exoticindiaart.com |date=2008-10-02 |accessdate=2012-01-05}}</ref>\n* 1976. \"Perversions&nbsp;\u2014 some observations\", ''Israel Ann. Psychiat. rel. Disc.'', (1976b), '''14''', 354-61.\n* 1976. (with Terri C. Masson) \"The Navel of Neurosis: Trauma, Memory and Denial\", paper presented to the San Francisco Psychoanalytic Society<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.enotes.com/psychoanalysis-encyclopedia/san-francisco-psychoanalytic-society-institute |title=San Francisco Psychoanalytic Society and Institute |publisher=Enotes.com |date= |accessdate=2012-01-05}}</ref>\n* 1978. (with Terri C. Masson) \"Buried Memories on the Acropolis. Freud's Relation to [[Mysticism]] and Anti-Semitism\", ''International Journal of Psycho-Analysis'' 59: 199-208.\n* 1980. ''The Oceanic Feeling: The Origins of [[Religion|Religious Sentiment]] in Ancient India''.\n* 1981. ''The Peacock's Egg: Love Poems from Ancient India'', [[W. S. Merwin]] and J. Moussaieff Masson, eds. {{ISBN|0-86547-059-6}}\n* 1984. ''The Assault on Truth: Freud's Suppression of the Seduction Theory''. [[Farrar Straus & Giroux]]. {{ISBN|0-374-10642-8}}\n* 1984. \"[https://www.theatlantic.com/issues/84feb/masson.htm Freud and the Seduction Theory A challenge to the foundations of psychoanalysis,]\" ''[[The Atlantic Monthly]]'', February 1984.\n* 1985. (editor) ''The Complete Letters of [[Sigmund Freud]] to [[Wilhelm Fliess]], 1887-1904''. {{ISBN|0-674-15420-7}}\n* 1986. ''A Dark Science: Women, Sexuality and Psychiatry in the Nineteenth Century''. {{ISBN|0-374-13501-0}}\n* 1988. ''[[Against Therapy]]: Emotional Tyranny and the Myth of Psychological Healing''. {{ISBN|0-689-11929-1}}\n* 1990. ''Final Analysis: The Making and Unmaking of A Psychoanalyst''. [[Addison-Wesley]]. {{ISBN|0-201-52368-X}}\n* 1993. ''My Father's Guru: A Journey Through Spirituality and Disillusion'', Addison-Wesley. {{ISBN|0-201-56778-4}}\n* 1994. (with Susan McCarthy) ''When Elephants Weep: The Emotional Life of Animals'', [[Jonathan Cape]].\n* 1995. \"[http://www.well.com/user/jct/masson.html A Note on U.G. Krishnamurti]\"\n* 1996. ''Lost Prince : The Unsolved Mystery of [[Kaspar Hauser]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=<!-- field: -->Barry J. Landau<!-- field: --> |url=http://www.pep-web.org/document.php?id=paq.067.0333a |title=Review |publisher=Pep-web.org |date= |accessdate=2012-01-05}}</ref>\n* 1997. ''Dogs Never Lie About Love: Reflections on the Emotional World of Dogs''.\n* 1999. ''The Emperor's Embrace: Reflections on Animal Families and Fatherhood''.\n* 2003. ''The Pig Who Sang to the Moon: The Emotional World of Farm Animals''.\n* 2002. ''The Nine Emotional Lives of Cats: A Journey Into the Feline Heart''. {{ISBN|0-345-44882-0}}\n* 2004. ''The Evolution of Fatherhood: A Celebration of Animal and Human Families''.\n* 2004. ''Slipping into Paradise: Why I live in New Zealand''. {{ISBN|0-345-46634-9}}\n* 2004. ''The Cat Who Came in from the Cold''. Wheeler. {{ISBN|1-58724-914-6}}\n* 2005. ''Raising the Peaceable Kingdom: What Animals Can Teach Us about the Social Origins of Tolerance and Friendship''.\n* 2006. ''Altruistic [[Armadillos]] - Zen-Like [[Zebra]]s: A Menagerie of 100 Favorite Animals''. {{ISBN|978-0-345-47881-8}}\n* 2009. ''The Face on Your Plate: The Truth about Food''. {{ISBN|978-0-393-06595-4}}\n* 2010. \"On Alice Miller\"<ref>Responding to [[Daphne Merkin]]'s article [http://www.tabletmag.com/arts-and-culture/books/32682/high-drama/ \"Private Drama\"] at ''[[Tablet Magazine]]''.</ref>\n* 2010. ''The Dog Who Couldn't Stop Loving: How Dogs Have Captured Our Hearts for Thousands of Years''. {{ISBN|978-0-06-177109-5}}\n* 2010. (editor) Sigmund Freud: ''[[The Interpretation of Dreams]]: The Illustrated Edition''. {{ISBN|978-1-4027-6388-5}}\n* 2010 ''Altruistic Armadillos, Zenlike Zebras-Understanding the World's Most Intriguing Animals''. [[Skyhorse Publishing]]. {{ISBN|1602397384}}\n* 2011. \"Pornography and animals\", in {{Cite book | editor-last1 = Tankard Reist | editor-first1 = Melinda | editor-last2 = Bray | editor-first2 = Abigail | editor-link1 = Melinda Tankard Reist | title = Big Porn Inc.: exposing the harms of the global pornography industry | pages = 63\u201368 | publisher = Spinifex Press | location = North Melbourne, Victoria | year = 2011 | isbn = 9781876756895 }}\n* 2014 ''Beasts: What Animals Can Teach Us About the Origins of Good and Evil''. [[Bloomsbury Publishing]]. {{ISBN|978-1608196159}}\n\n=== Reviews of his books ===\n* <cite>''The Original Letters of [[Sigmund Freud]] to [[Wilhelm Fliess]] 1887-1904''</cite>: [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=940DEEDC1F38F93BA15757C0A963948260 By William McGrath.]\n* <cite>''Against Therapy''</cite>:\n** [http://www.adpca.org/Journal/Vol1_1/against.htm By Jeanne Stubbs.]\n** [https://web.archive.org/web/20070308004053/http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1175/is_n10_v22/ai_6652874 By Wray Herbert.]\n* <cite>''Final Analysis''</cite>: [http://www.pep-web.org/document.php?id=apa.041.0306a By Michael Sacks.]\n* <cite>''Breaking Away From the Cult''</cite>: [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C0CE4D6153FF932A15753C1A966958260 By Carol Tavris.]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of vegans]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book |first=Kurt R. |last=Eissler |year=2001 |title=Freud and the seduction theory: A brief love affair |location=New York |publisher=International Universities Press}}\n* {{cite news |date=6 February 1984 |first=John |last=Lee |authorlink=John Lee (author) |title=Trying to Rock the Couch: An analyst charges that Freud suppressed a key theory |journal=Time |page=58}}\n* {{cite book |first=Janet |last=Malcolm |authorlink=Janet Malcolm |year=2002 |title=In the Freud Archives |publisher=[[New York Review of Books]] |isbn=1-59017-027-X}}\n* {{cite book |first=Luna |last=Tarlo |year=1997 |title=The Mother of God |publisher=Plover Press |isbn=978-1-57027-043-7}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.jeffreymasson.com Jeffrey Masson's website]\n\n;Articles\n* \"[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?sec=health&res=9E06E3D8153BF93BA2575BC0A967948260&n=Top%2fReference%2fTimes%20Topics%2fPeople%2fB%2fBlumenthal%2c%20Ralph Scholars seek the hidden Freud in newly emerging letters.]\" The first of two ''[[NYT]]'' articles by Ralph Blumenthal, published August 18, 1981.\n* \"[http://www.robertboynton.com/articleDisplay.php?article_id=20 Till Press Do Us Part: The Trial of Janet Malcolm and Jeffrey Masson.]\"\n'''Interviews'''\n* [http://www.abc.net.au/rn/scienceshow/stories/2006/1652467.htm Transcript] of an interview: Jeffrey Masson talking with [[Kirsten Garrett]] about Sigmund Freud and [[Emma Eckstein]]/ first broadcast on ''The Science Show'' in 1986, second broadcast 3 June 2006 presented by [[Robyn Williams]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120319220020/http://www.charlierose.com/guest/view/4897 A conversation about the lives of animals] with Susan McCarthy and Jeffrey Moussaieff Mason on Jun 30, 1995, Duration 60 min (Audio)\n* \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20110629103347/http://www.powells.com/authors/masson.html Walking on the Beach with Jeffrey Masson's Cats,]\" November 14, 2002\n* \"[http://www.abc.net.au/queensland/conversations/stories/s2119416.htm?queensland Conversation] between Masson and Richard Fidler. Related Audio, December 14, 2007.\n* \"[http://knowinganimals.libsyn.com/episode-6-human-and-the-beast-with-jeffrey-masson Episode 6: Human and the Beast]\", Masson interviewed by [[Siobhan O'Sullivan]] for the ''Knowing Animals'' podcast\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Masson, Jeffrey Moussaieff}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American people of French-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Animal rights scholars]]\n[[Category:Anti-psychiatry]]\n[[Category:Writers from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan faculty]]\n[[Category:Veganism activists]]\n[[Category:American memoirists]]\n[[Category:American autobiographers]]\n[[Category:American psychoanalysts]]\n[[Category:Jewish psychoanalysts]]\n[[Category:American Sanskrit scholars]]\n[[Category:University of Toronto faculty]]\n[[Category:Brown University faculty]]\n[[Category:After Dark (British TV series) participants]]\n[[Category:Translators of Sigmund Freud]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer  <!--For more information, see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]].-->\n| name = Jeffrey Moussaieff Masson\n| honorific_prefix = \n| honorific_suffix = \n| image = Jeffrey_Moussaieff_Masson.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Appearing on the UK TV programme ''[[After Dark (TV series)|After Dark]]'' in 1989\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| pseudonym = \n| birth_name = Jeffrey Lloyd Masson\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1941|03|28}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date =    <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place = \n| resting_place = \n| occupation = \n| language = \n| nationality = American\n| ethnicity = \n| citizenship = \n| education = \n| alma_mater = [[Harvard University]]\n| period = \n| genre =\n| subject = [[Psychoanalysis]]\n| movement = \n| notablework = ''[[The Assault on Truth]]'' (1984)\n| spouse =        <!-- or: | spouses =     -->\n| partner =       <!-- or: | partners =    -->\n| children = \n| relatives = \n| awards = \n| signature = \n| signature_alt = \n| years_active = \n| module = \n| website = \n| portaldisp =    <!-- \"on\", \"yes\", \"true\", etc; or omit -->\n}}\n'''Jeffrey Moussaieff Masson''' (born March 28, 1941 as '''Jeffrey Lloyd Masson''') is an American author. Masson is best known for his conclusions about [[Sigmund Freud]] and [[psychoanalysis]]. In his ''[[The Assault on Truth]]'' (1984), Masson argues that Freud may have abandoned his [[Freud's seduction theory|seduction theory]] because he feared that granting the truth of his female patients' claims (that they had been [[sexual abuse|sexually abused]]) would hinder the acceptance of his [[psychoanalysis|psychoanalytic]] methods. Masson is a [[veganism]] advocate and has written about [[animal rights]].<ref name=Jeff>{{cite web|url=http://www.jeffreymasson.com/about.html |title=About Jeff |publisher=Jeffreymasson.com |date= |accessdate=2012-01-05}}</ref>\n\n== Life and career ==\nJeffrey Masson is the son of Jacques Masson, a Frenchman of [[Bukharian Jew|Bukharian]] ancestry, and Diana (Dina) Zeiger from an [[Ashkenazi]] strict [[Orthodox Jew]]ish family. Both of his parents were followers of the [[guru]] [[Paul Brunton]].<ref name=\"NY\"/> Masson's mother later became a follower of [[Mysticism|mystic]] [[John Levy (philosopher)|John Levy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ods.nl/am1gos/am1gos5/index.html?jl_vriend_us.html~mainFrame |title=John Levy: friend and contrary guru |publisher=Ods.nl |date= |accessdate=2012-01-05}}</ref> During the 1940s and 1950s, Brunton often lived with them, eventually designating Masson as his [[heir apparent]]. In 1956, Diana and Jacques Masson moved to [[Uruguay]] because Brunton believed that a [[World War III|third world war]] was imminent. Jeffrey and his sister Linda followed in 1959.\n\nAt Brunton's urging, Masson went to [[Harvard University]] to study [[Sanskrit]]. While at Harvard, Masson became disillusioned with Brunton. Brunton and his influence on the Masson family form the subject of Masson's autobiographical book ''My Father's Guru: A Journey Through Spirituality and Disillusion''. [[Harvard University]] granted Masson a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in 1964 and a [[Ph.D.]] with Honors in 1970. His degrees were in [[Sanskrit]] and [[Indian Studies]]. While undertaking his Ph.D., Masson also studied, supported by fellowships, at the [[\u00c9cole Normale Sup\u00e9rieure]] in Paris, the [[University of Calcutta]], and the [[University of Poona]].\n\nMasson taught Sanskrit and Indian Studies at the [[University of Toronto]], 1969\u201380, reaching the rank of Professor. He has also held short term appointments at [[Brown University]], the [[University of California]], and the [[University of Michigan]]. From 1981 to 1992, he was a Research Associate, Department of South and Southeast Asian Studies, at the [[University of California, Berkeley]]. He is currently an Honorary Fellow in the Department of [[Philosophy]] at the [[University of Auckland]] in New Zealand.\n\n== Views on Freud's seduction theory ==\nIn 1970, Masson began studying to become a psychoanalyst at the Toronto Psychoanalytic Institute, completing a full clinical training course in 1978. His training analyst was Irvine Schiffer, a well-known Toronto analyst and author of books on the unconscious aspects of charisma and time. In 1990 Masson published an autobiographical book in which he accused Schiffer of cursing, being constantly late for sessions, and intimidating Masson when the latter complained about this issue.<ref name=\"Final Analysis\">{{cite book |last=Masson |first=Jeffrey |year=1990 |title=Final Analysis: The Making and Unmaking of a Psychoanalyst |publisher=Addison-Wesley |isbn=0-201-52368-X}}</ref> Schiffer denied it and debated Masson on the Canadian television program ''[[The Fifth Estate (TV)|The Fifth Estate]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=61MAAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA40 | title=Love is Strange | publisher=([[Google Books]]) | work=[[New York Magazine]] | date=March 22, 1993 | accessdate=November 14, 2012 | author=Smith, Dinitia}}</ref>\n\nDuring this time, Masson befriended the psychoanalyst [[Kurt Eissler]] and became acquainted with [[Sigmund Freud]]'s daughter [[Anna Freud]]. Eissler designated Masson to succeed him as Director of the [[Sigmund Freud Archives]] after his and Anna Freud's death. Masson learned [[German language|German]] and studied the [[history of psychoanalysis]]. In 1980 Masson was appointed Projects Director of the Freud Archives, with full access to Freud's correspondence and other unpublished papers. While perusing this material, Masson concluded that Freud might have rejected the seduction theory in order to advance the cause of [[psychoanalysis]] and to maintain his own place within the psychoanalytic inner circle, after a hostile response from the renowned sex-pathologist [[Richard von Krafft-Ebing]] and the rest of the Vienna Psychiatric Society in 1896 - \"an icy reception from the jackasses,\" was the way Freud described it later to Fliess\n<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?sec=health&res=9A0CEFDA123BF936A1575BC0A967948260 \"Did Freud's Isolation Lead Him to Reverse Theory on Neurosis?\"] by Ralph Blumenthal, ''[[New York Times]]'', August 25, 1981</ref>\n\nIn 1981, Masson's controversial conclusions were discussed in a series of ''[[New York Times]]'' articles by Ralph Blumenthal, to the dismay of the psychoanalytic establishment. Masson was subsequently dismissed from his position as project director of the Freud Archives and stripped of his membership in psychoanalytic professional societies. Masson was defended by [[Alice Miller (psychologist)|Alice Miller]]<ref>PSYCHOLOGIE HEUTE, April 1987, P.21, 22: \"Im Gegensatz zu manchen Interpreten, die, wie zum Beispiel Marianne Kr\u00fcll, Marie Balmary oder Jeffrey Masson, Freuds Abkehr von der Wahrheit als Folge seiner Familiengeschichte deuten, sehe ich diesen Schritt als Folge und Ausdruck unserer jahrtausendealten kinderfeindlichen Tradition, in der wir auch heute noch leben. Die Ergebnisse der oben genannten historischen Forscher k\u00f6nnen trotzdem korrekt sein, aber ich meine, da\u00df es Freud trotz der pers\u00f6nlichen Familiengeschichte m\u00f6glich gewesen w\u00e4re, seiner Entdeckung treu zu bleiben, wenn die Gesellschaft als Ganzes nicht so kinderfeindlich gewesen w\u00e4re, wenn schon damals andere, freiere Erziehungsmuster denkbar gewesen w\u00e4ren. Doch zur Zeit Freuds war es noch absolut unm\u00f6glich, die Unschuld der Eltern in Frage zu stellen.\" Alice Miller in interview entitled ''Wie Psychotherapien das Kind verraten''</ref>\nand [[Muriel Gardiner]] (\"While striving not to take sides,\" Gardiner said, \"I consider him a good and energetic worker and a worthwhile scholar\").<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?sec=health&res=9400E3DA1E39F93AA35752C1A967948260 \"Freud Archives Research Chief Removed in Dispute Over Yale Talk\"] by Ralph Blumenthal, ''[[New York Times]]'' November 9, 1981.</ref>\n\nMasson later wrote several books critical of psychoanalysis, including ''The Assault on Truth: Freud's Suppression of the Seduction Theory''. In the introduction to ''The Assault on Truth'', Masson challenged his critics to address his arguments: \"My pessimistic conclusions may possibly be wrong. The documents may in fact allow a very different reading.\"<ref>{{cite book |first=Jeffrey |last=Masson |year=1992 |title=The Assault on Truth: Freud's Suppression of the Seduction Theory |publisher=Harper Perennial |location=New York |isbn= 0-06-097457-5 |pages= xxxv |nopp=true}}</ref> [[Janet Malcolm]] interviewed Masson at length when writing her long ''[[The New Yorker|New Yorker]]'' article on this controversy, which she later expanded into ''[[In the Freud Archives]]'', a book that also dealt with Eissler and [[Peter Swales (historian)|Peter Swales]]. Masson sued ''The New Yorker'' for [[defamation]], claiming that Malcolm had misquoted him. The ensuing trial drew considerable attention.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Psychoanalyst Loses Libel Suit Against a New Yorker Reporter | work = [[The New York Times]] | date = 1994-11-03 | author = David Margolick}}</ref> The decade-long, [[US$]]10 million lawsuit came to a close in 1994 when the court ruled in ''The New Yorker'' 's favor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/books/the-journalist-and-the-biographer/2007/10/04/1191091267930.html?page=fullpage#contentSwap2 |title=SMH article October 6, 2007 |publisher=Smh.com.au |date=2007-10-06 |accessdate=2012-01-05}}</ref> \"The Court of Appeals affirmed ... that Malcolm had deliberately altered each quotation not found on the tape recordings, but nevertheless held that petitioner failed to raise a jury question of actual malice.\"<ref>{{Cite web|title=Masson v. New Yorker Magazine, Inc. (89-1799), 501 U.S. 496 (1991)|url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/supct/html/89-1799.ZO.html|work=Masson v. New Yorker Magazine, Inc. (89-1799), 501 U.S. 496 (1991)|publisher=Supreme Court/Cornell University Law School|year=1991|accessdate=Oct 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985, Masson edited and translated Freud's complete correspondence with [[Wilhelm Fliess]] after having convinced Anna Freud to make it available in full. He also looked up the original places and documents in La [[Salp\u00eatri\u00e8re]] Hospital in Paris,<ref>[http://www.paris.org/Kiosque/sep98/la.salpetriere.html History of La Salp\u00eatri\u00e8re] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110103105500/http://www.paris.org/Kiosque/sep98/la.salpetriere.html |date=January 3, 2011 }}</ref> where Freud had studied with [[Jean-Martin Charcot|Charcot]]. Masson writes that the scientific community has been largely silent about his views, and that he suffered personal attacks once he deviated from the traditional views on the seduction theory and the history of psychoanalysis.<ref name=\"Final Analysis\"/> Both the traditional view and Masson's case against it are built on the account that Freud's seduction theory patients reported having been sexually abused in early childhood; several Freud scholars have disputed this account <ref>Schimek, J. G. (1987). Fact and Fantasy in the Seduction Theory: a Historical Review. ''Journal of the American Psychoanalytic Association'', xxxv: 937-65; Isra\u00ebls, H. and Schatzman, M. (1993) The Seduction Theory. ''History of Psychiatry'', iv: 23-59; Esterson, A. (1998). [http://human-nature.com/esterson/synopsis.html Jeffrey Masson and Freud\u2019s seduction theory: a new fable based on old myths]. ''History of the Human Sciences'', 11 (1), pp. 1-21; Esterson, A. (2001). The mythologizing of psychoanalytic history: deception and self deception in Freud's accounts of the seduction theory episode. ''History of Psychiatry'', Vol. 12 (3), pp. 329-352; Eissler, K. R. (2001) ''Freud and the Seduction Theory: A Brief Love Affair.'' International Universities Press, pp. 107-117.</ref>\n\n== Recent work ==\nSince the early 1990s, Masson has written a number of books on the emotional life of animals, one of which, ''When Elephants Weep'', has been translated into 20 languages. He has explained this radical change in the subject of his writings as follows:\n\n{{quote|I'd written a whole series of books about [[psychiatry]], and nobody bought them. Nobody liked them. Nobody. Psychiatrists hated them, and they were much too abstruse for the general public. It was very hard to make a living, and I thought, \"As long as I'm not making a living, I may as well write about something I really love: animals.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.powells.com/authors/masson.html |title=Interviews&nbsp;\u2014 Jeffrey Masson |publisher=Powells.com |date= |access-date=2012-01-05 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629103347/http://www.powells.com/authors/masson.html |archive-date=2011-06-29 |df= }}</ref>}}\n\nIn 2008, Masson became a Director of [[Voiceless, the animal protection institute]].  \"We are not encouraged, on a daily basis, to pay careful attention to the animals we eat. On the contrary, the meat, dairy, and egg industries all actively encourage us to give thought to our own immediate interest (taste, for example, or cheap food) but not to the real suffering involved ... The animals involved suffer agony because of our ignorance. The least we owe them is to lessen that ignorance\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Voiceless, the animal protection institute|url=https://www.voiceless.org.au/who-we-are/jeffrey-masson}}</ref>\n\nMasson also wrote a book about living in New Zealand, including an interview with Sir [[Edmund Hillary]].<ref>Masson, J., \"A Conversation with a Great Ordinary Kiwi: Sir Edmund Hillary,\" chpt. 7 in ''Slipping into Paradise''.</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nMasson is married to Leila Masson, a German [[pediatrics|pediatrician]].<ref name=\"NY\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leilamasson.com |title=Dr. Leila Masson |publisher=Leilamasson.com |date= |accessdate=2012-01-05}}</ref> They have two sons. He also has a daughter by a previous marriage with Therese Claire Masson.<ref name=Jeff/> In the early 1990s, Masson had been engaged to [[University of Michigan]] [[feminist]] legal scholar [[Catharine MacKinnon]], who wrote the preface to his ''A Dark Science: Women, Sexuality, and Psychiatry in the Nineteenth Century''.<ref>{{Cite news| volume = 26| issue = 12| pages = 36\u201343| last = Smith| first = Dinitia| title = Love is Strange: The Crusading Feminist and the Repentant Womanizer| work = [[New York Magazine|New York]]| accessdate = 2010-02-14| date = 1993-03-22| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=61MAAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA36&pg=PA36#v=onepage&q=&f=false}} ([https://books.google.com/books?id=61MAAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q=&f=false cover])</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2006/apr/12/gender.politicsphilosophyandsociety \"Are women human?\"] by Stuart Jeffries, ''[[The Guardian]]'', April 12, 2006.</ref>\n\nMasson became a [[veganism|vegan]] in 2004.<ref name=\"NY\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/15/dining/15mass.html?pagewanted=all |title=A Man With Opinions on Food With a Face |first=Eric |last=Konigsberg |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=14 April 2009 |accessdate=19 April 2012}}</ref> He is an [[animal rights]] activist.<ref name=Jeff/>\n\n== Name ==\nMasson's great-grandfather [[Shlomo Moussaieff (rabbi)|Shlomo Moussaieff]] was a [[Kabbalah|kabbalist]] and founder of the [[Bukharim|Bukharian Quarter]] in [[Jerusalem]]. His grandfather Henry Mousaieff changed his family name from Moussaieff to Masson. Masson changed his middle name from Lloyd to Moussaieff.<ref name=Moussaieff>Wagner, Frank D. (2004). [https://books.google.com/books?id=Jf-6mBUJHp0C&pg=PA504&lpg=PA504&dq=Jeffrey+Moussaieff+Masson+%22his+middle+name%22&source=bl&ots=7e52RezlBt&sig=ACfU3U3XHzemNwsnpq7nHnb3K38HHId6LA&hl=en&ppis=_e&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjVr63_8_XnAhVWhHIEHQevAkUQ6AEwB3oECBYQAQ#v=onepage&q=Jeffrey%20Moussaieff%20Masson%20%22his%20middle%20name%22&f=false ''United States Reports: Cases Adjudged in the Supreme Court'']. Washington, DC: U.S. Government Printing Office. p. 504. {{ISBN|0-16-048116-3}}.</ref>\n\n== Works ==\n* 1974. \"India and the Unconscious: Erik Erikson on Gandhi,\" ''[[International Journal of Psycho-Analysis]]'' 55: 519-26. Discussion by T. C. Sinha: 527.\n* 1974. \"Sex and Yoga: Psychoanalysis and the Indian Religious Experience\", ''[[Journal of Indian Philosophy]]'' 2: 307\u2013320. Reprinted in ''Vishnu on Freud's Desk: A Reader in Psychoanalysis and Hinduism'', T.G. Vaidyanathan and [[Jeffrey J. Kripal]] eds. [[Oxford University Press]], {{ISBN|0-19-565835-3}}, Paperback (Edition: 2003)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exoticindiaart.com/book/details/IDG634/ |title=Table of Contents |publisher=Exoticindiaart.com |date=2008-10-02 |accessdate=2012-01-05}}</ref>\n* 1976. \"Perversions&nbsp;\u2014 some observations\", ''Israel Ann. Psychiat. rel. Disc.'', (1976b), '''14''', 354-61.\n* 1976. (with Terri C. Masson) \"The Navel of Neurosis: Trauma, Memory and Denial\", paper presented to the San Francisco Psychoanalytic Society<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.enotes.com/psychoanalysis-encyclopedia/san-francisco-psychoanalytic-society-institute |title=San Francisco Psychoanalytic Society and Institute |publisher=Enotes.com |date= |accessdate=2012-01-05}}</ref>\n* 1978. (with Terri C. Masson) \"Buried Memories on the Acropolis. Freud's Relation to [[Mysticism]] and Anti-Semitism\", ''International Journal of Psycho-Analysis'' 59: 199-208.\n* 1980. ''The Oceanic Feeling: The Origins of [[Religion|Religious Sentiment]] in Ancient India''.\n* 1981. ''The Peacock's Egg: Love Poems from Ancient India'', [[W. S. Merwin]] and J. Moussaieff Masson, eds. {{ISBN|0-86547-059-6}}\n* 1984. ''The Assault on Truth: Freud's Suppression of the Seduction Theory''. [[Farrar Straus & Giroux]]. {{ISBN|0-374-10642-8}}\n* 1984. \"[https://www.theatlantic.com/issues/84feb/masson.htm Freud and the Seduction Theory A challenge to the foundations of psychoanalysis,]\" ''[[The Atlantic Monthly]]'', February 1984.\n* 1985. (editor) ''The Complete Letters of [[Sigmund Freud]] to [[Wilhelm Fliess]], 1887-1904''. {{ISBN|0-674-15420-7}}\n* 1986. ''A Dark Science: Women, Sexuality and Psychiatry in the Nineteenth Century''. {{ISBN|0-374-13501-0}}\n* 1988. ''[[Against Therapy]]: Emotional Tyranny and the Myth of Psychological Healing''. {{ISBN|0-689-11929-1}}\n* 1990. ''Final Analysis: The Making and Unmaking of A Psychoanalyst''. [[Addison-Wesley]]. {{ISBN|0-201-52368-X}}\n* 1993. ''My Father's Guru: A Journey Through Spirituality and Disillusion'', Addison-Wesley. {{ISBN|0-201-56778-4}}\n* 1994. (with Susan McCarthy) ''When Elephants Weep: The Emotional Life of Animals'', [[Jonathan Cape]].\n* 1995. \"[http://www.well.com/user/jct/masson.html A Note on U.G. Krishnamurti]\"\n* 1996. ''Lost Prince : The Unsolved Mystery of [[Kaspar Hauser]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=<!-- field: -->Barry J. Landau<!-- field: --> |url=http://www.pep-web.org/document.php?id=paq.067.0333a |title=Review |publisher=Pep-web.org |date= |accessdate=2012-01-05}}</ref>\n* 1997. ''Dogs Never Lie About Love: Reflections on the Emotional World of Dogs''.\n* 1999. ''The Emperor's Embrace: Reflections on Animal Families and Fatherhood''.\n* 2003. ''The Pig Who Sang to the Moon: The Emotional World of Farm Animals''.\n* 2002. ''The Nine Emotional Lives of Cats: A Journey Into the Feline Heart''. {{ISBN|0-345-44882-0}}\n* 2004. ''The Evolution of Fatherhood: A Celebration of Animal and Human Families''.\n* 2004. ''Slipping into Paradise: Why I live in New Zealand''. {{ISBN|0-345-46634-9}}\n* 2004. ''The Cat Who Came in from the Cold''. Wheeler. {{ISBN|1-58724-914-6}}\n* 2005. ''Raising the Peaceable Kingdom: What Animals Can Teach Us about the Social Origins of Tolerance and Friendship''.\n* 2006. ''Altruistic [[Armadillos]] - Zen-Like [[Zebra]]s: A Menagerie of 100 Favorite Animals''. {{ISBN|978-0-345-47881-8}}\n* 2009. ''The Face on Your Plate: The Truth about Food''. {{ISBN|978-0-393-06595-4}}\n* 2010. \"On Alice Miller\"<ref>Responding to [[Daphne Merkin]]'s article [http://www.tabletmag.com/arts-and-culture/books/32682/high-drama/ \"Private Drama\"] at ''[[Tablet Magazine]]''.</ref>\n* 2010. ''The Dog Who Couldn't Stop Loving: How Dogs Have Captured Our Hearts for Thousands of Years''. {{ISBN|978-0-06-177109-5}}\n* 2010. (editor) Sigmund Freud: ''[[The Interpretation of Dreams]]: The Illustrated Edition''. {{ISBN|978-1-4027-6388-5}}\n* 2010 ''Altruistic Armadillos, Zenlike Zebras-Understanding the World's Most Intriguing Animals''. [[Skyhorse Publishing]]. {{ISBN|1602397384}}\n* 2011. \"Pornography and animals\", in {{Cite book | editor-last1 = Tankard Reist | editor-first1 = Melinda | editor-last2 = Bray | editor-first2 = Abigail | editor-link1 = Melinda Tankard Reist | title = Big Porn Inc.: exposing the harms of the global pornography industry | pages = 63\u201368 | publisher = Spinifex Press | location = North Melbourne, Victoria | year = 2011 | isbn = 9781876756895 }}\n* 2014 ''Beasts: What Animals Can Teach Us About the Origins of Good and Evil''. [[Bloomsbury Publishing]]. {{ISBN|978-1608196159}}\n\n=== Reviews of his books ===\n* <cite>''The Original Letters of [[Sigmund Freud]] to [[Wilhelm Fliess]] 1887-1904''</cite>: [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=940DEEDC1F38F93BA15757C0A963948260 By William McGrath.]\n* <cite>''Against Therapy''</cite>:\n** [http://www.adpca.org/Journal/Vol1_1/against.htm By Jeanne Stubbs.]\n** [https://web.archive.org/web/20070308004053/http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1175/is_n10_v22/ai_6652874 By Wray Herbert.]\n* <cite>''Final Analysis''</cite>: [http://www.pep-web.org/document.php?id=apa.041.0306a By Michael Sacks.]\n* <cite>''Breaking Away From the Cult''</cite>: [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C0CE4D6153FF932A15753C1A966958260 By Carol Tavris.]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of vegans]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book |first=Kurt R. |last=Eissler |year=2001 |title=Freud and the seduction theory: A brief love affair |location=New York |publisher=International Universities Press}}\n* {{cite news |date=6 February 1984 |first=John |last=Lee |authorlink=John Lee (author) |title=Trying to Rock the Couch: An analyst charges that Freud suppressed a key theory |journal=Time |page=58}}\n* {{cite book |first=Janet |last=Malcolm |authorlink=Janet Malcolm |year=2002 |title=In the Freud Archives |publisher=[[New York Review of Books]] |isbn=1-59017-027-X}}\n* {{cite book |first=Luna |last=Tarlo |year=1997 |title=The Mother of God |publisher=Plover Press |isbn=978-1-57027-043-7}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.jeffreymasson.com Jeffrey Masson's website]\n\n;Articles\n* \"[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?sec=health&res=9E06E3D8153BF93BA2575BC0A967948260&n=Top%2fReference%2fTimes%20Topics%2fPeople%2fB%2fBlumenthal%2c%20Ralph Scholars seek the hidden Freud in newly emerging letters.]\" The first of two ''[[NYT]]'' articles by Ralph Blumenthal, published August 18, 1981.\n* \"[http://www.robertboynton.com/articleDisplay.php?article_id=20 Till Press Do Us Part: The Trial of Janet Malcolm and Jeffrey Masson.]\"\n'''Interviews'''\n* [http://www.abc.net.au/rn/scienceshow/stories/2006/1652467.htm Transcript] of an interview: Jeffrey Masson talking with [[Kirsten Garrett]] about Sigmund Freud and [[Emma Eckstein]]/ first broadcast on ''The Science Show'' in 1986, second broadcast 3 June 2006 presented by [[Robyn Williams]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120319220020/http://www.charlierose.com/guest/view/4897 A conversation about the lives of animals] with Susan McCarthy and Jeffrey Moussaieff Mason on Jun 30, 1995, Duration 60 min (Audio)\n* \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20110629103347/http://www.powells.com/authors/masson.html Walking on the Beach with Jeffrey Masson's Cats,]\" November 14, 2002\n* \"[http://www.abc.net.au/queensland/conversations/stories/s2119416.htm?queensland Conversation] between Masson and Richard Fidler. Related Audio, December 14, 2007.\n* \"[http://knowinganimals.libsyn.com/episode-6-human-and-the-beast-with-jeffrey-masson Episode 6: Human and the Beast]\", Masson interviewed by [[Siobhan O'Sullivan]] for the ''Knowing Animals'' podcast\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Masson, Jeffrey Moussaieff}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American people of French-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Animal rights scholars]]\n[[Category:Anti-psychiatry]]\n[[Category:Writers from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan faculty]]\n[[Category:Veganism activists]]\n[[Category:American memoirists]]\n[[Category:American autobiographers]]\n[[Category:American psychoanalysts]]\n[[Category:Jewish psychoanalysts]]\n[[Category:American Sanskrit scholars]]\n[[Category:University of Toronto faculty]]\n[[Category:Brown University faculty]]\n[[Category:After Dark (British TV series) participants]]\n[[Category:Translators of Sigmund Freud]]\n", "name_user": "NONIS STEFANO", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eViews on Freud's seduction theory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeffrey_Moussaieff_Masson"}
{"title_page": "Lisa Goes Gaga", "text_new": "{{Good article}}\n{{Infobox Simpsons episode\n| title          = Lisa Goes Gaga\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| season         = 23\n| episode        = 22 \n| director       = [[Matthew Schofield]]\n| writer         = [[Tim Long]]\n| production     = PABF14\n| airdate        = {{Start date|2012|05|20}}\n| guests         = [[Lady Gaga]] as herself<br/>[[Kevin Michael Richardson]] as Lady Gaga Express Conductor\n| blackboard     = \n| couch_gag      = The family are playing a [[Nintendo Wii|Zii]] game in which they sit on the couch, but Homer keeps failing. Homer angrily throws his controller down and tries to sit on the real couch, but fails just like in the game.\n| commentary     = \n| prev           = [[Ned 'n' Edna's Blend Agenda]]\n| next           = [[Moonshine River]]\n}}\n\"'''Lisa Goes Gaga'''\" is the twenty-second and final episode of the [[The Simpsons (season 23)|twenty-third season]] of the American animated sitcom ''[[The Simpsons]]''. It originally aired on the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox network]] in the United States on May 20, 2012. In the episode, American singer-songwriter [[Lady Gaga]] makes a visit to Springfield, where all of its residents are in a state of depression. Main character [[Lisa Simpson]] is arguably the most depressed person in the city, prompting Gaga to go out of her way to teach Lisa the meaning of happiness.\n\nThe episode was written by [[Tim Long]] and directed by Matthew Schofield. Gaga guest-starred in the episode, portraying an animated version of herself. A fan of the show, she was brought on by showrunner [[Al Jean]], who wrote a script after [[James L. Brooks]] saw an interview of her on ''[[60 Minutes]]''. The design team conceived eighteen outfits to complement Gaga's eccentric persona, which satirized several of her outfits including her [[Lady Gaga's meat dress|meat dress]]. Recording sessions for \"Lisa Goes Gaga\" took place in [[Los Angeles, California]] over four days in August 2011. \n\nCritical responses to the episode were mixed to negative; critics praised Lady Gaga's performance, while they looked down upon the episode's concept and general execution. According to the [[Nielsen ratings]], the installment attained 4.79 million American viewers upon its original airing.\n\n==Plot==\n[[Lady Gaga]] passes through [[Springfield (The Simpsons)|Springfield]] via train while on her way to a concert.  Seeing how low the city's self-esteem is, she takes it upon herself to cheer up the whole city. However, no one in town is more depressed than [[Lisa Simpson|Lisa]], who was voted as the most unpopular student by her peers. Lisa tries to reverse her status as one of the least popular girls in school by ghostwriting positive things about herself on the school blog under the heading \"Truth Teller\".\n\nWhen [[Bart Simpson|Bart]] finds out her secret and reveals it to the school, her social ranking plummets to a new low until a psychic force tells Lady Gaga that Lisa needs her help immediately. After much soul searching and yelling at Lady Gaga for trying to help, Lisa realizes that her outburst helped her because she is finally expressing her anger instead of bottling it up inside her, in effect making Lady Gaga's mission successful. Lisa catches Lady Gaga just before she leaves town to apologize, and after being forgiven she and Lady Gaga perform a duet together. With Lady Gaga's assistance, Lisa and the entire town of Springfield realize that being oneself is better than being like anyone else. Just as Lady Gaga's train begins to leave again, [[Moe Szyslak|Moe]] runs up to her and asks if she can help him as well, but Lady Gaga declines, stating that she's not that good. As Moe turns and walks across the train track, a second train hits him.<!--He appears in the following episode alive, \"Moonshine River\"-->\n\nDuring the credits, Homer is heard singing his rendition of \"[[Poker Face (Lady Gaga song)|Poker Face]]\".\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Gaga pyro bra 02.jpg|thumb|Gaga's Pyrotechnic Underwear was one of her outfits that was parodied in the episode.]]\n\nIn August 2011, it first was revealed that [[Lady Gaga]] would make a guest appearance on the show as herself.<ref name=EW>{{cite web|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2011/08/23/lady-gaga-the-simpsons-exclusive-photo/?iid=rcfooter-tv-%27simpsons%27+goes+gaga%3A+first+pic!|title=Lady Gaga to guest on 'The Simpsons' -- Exclusive Photo|last=Snierson|first= Dan|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time, Inc.]]|date=August 23, 2011|accessdate=August 23, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/news/lady-gaga-to-spice-up-the-simpsons-16041045.html|title=Lady Gaga to spice up The Simpsons|work=[[The Belfast Telegraph]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|date=August 25, 2011|accessdate=August 26, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/celebritology/post/lady-gaga-gets-animated-for-the-simpsons/2011/08/23/gIQA3B2CZJ_blog.html|title=Lady Gaga gets animated for \u2018The Simpsons\u2019|first=Sarah|last=Anne Hughes|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=August 23, 2011|accessdate=August 26, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/08/23/lady-gaga-to-guest-star-the-simpsons_n_934423.html|title=Lady Gaga To Guest-Star On 'The Simpsons'|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|publisher=[[Arianna Huffington]]|date=August 23, 2011|accessdate=August 26, 2011}}</ref> Producer [[James L. Brooks]] viewed Gaga's interview with [[Anderson Cooper]] on ''[[60 Minutes]]'', which prompted [[Al Jean]] to write a script and send her a letter of approval to appear on the show.<ref name=mtv2>{{cite web|url=http://style.mtv.com/2012/05/18/lady-gaga-the-simpsons/|title=Lady Gaga's 'The Simpsons' Style: Exclusive Interview With Executive Producer/Writer Al Jean|first=Gaby|last=Wilson|publisher=[[MTV]] ([[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]])|date=May 18, 2012|accessdate=May 20, 2012}}</ref> \"She was really excited about the whole thing,\" Jean recalled. \"After she signed on to do it, she came in to record dialogue twice, and we showed her a rough cut the second time.\"<ref name=mtv2/> Recording sessions for the episode took place in [[Los Angeles]] during a period of four days from August 22\u201326.<ref name=EW/> Gaga was initially apprehensive while recording on set, which led her to review the satirical nature of the show to get a better understanding on how to perform. \"Their characters are so awesomely convincing and sincere and wild and funny, I had to remind myself constantly of the sincerity of the humor,\" she explained. \"That's what I was trying to focus on\u2014not putting on a character too much, and really being as sincere as I could with the lines.\"<ref name=EW/> Despite such emotions, Gaga professed that working with the staff of the show was \"one of the coolest things that [she] has ever done\".<ref name=EW/>\n\nSeveral employees of ''The Simpsons'' were impressed with Gaga's performance, who cited that her vocal range and ad-libbing skills were exceptional. Series creator [[Matt Groening]] stated: \"Since the very beginning, I\u2019ve always wanted to have on the most iconic personalities of our time, and she's it.\"<ref name=EW/> In an interview with [[E! Online]], Groening further commented on Gaga's appearance; \"The great thing about having Lady Gaga is that she came in a number of times and always with a different getup. Like she'd leave the room and come back in after a break in a completely new getup. It was unbelievable. The only time that she ever took off her hat was when it was banging into the microphone.\"<ref name=e!>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/watch_with_kristin/jennifer_aniston_really_coming_cougar/193233 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20121208190236/http://www.eonline.com/news/watch_with_kristin/jennifer_aniston_really_coming_cougar/193233 |url-status=dead |archive-date=December 8, 2012 |title=The Simpsons Celebrates 500 Episodes: How Kooky Was Lady Gaga? And Which Big Stars Are Next? |first=Tierney |last=Bricker |publisher=[[E!]] |date=February 17, 2012 |accessdate=February 18, 2012 }}</ref> Cast member [[Yeardley Smith]] said that she was shocked that Gaga had the time to make an appearance on the series.<ref name=MTV>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1669502/lady-gaga-the-simpsons-guest.jhtml|title=Lady Gaga To Guest-Star On 'The Simpsons'|first=Jocelyn|last=Vena|publisher=[[MTV]] ([[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]])|date=August 23, 2011|accessdate=August 23, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe design team for the series conceived eighteen outfits to complement Gaga's [[wiktionary:outr\u00e9|outr\u00e9]] and eccentric reputation, although they did not collaborate with any of Gaga's stylists or creative director [[Nicola Formichetti]].<ref name=mtv22>{{cite web|url=http://newsroom.mtv.com/2012/05/18/simpsons-producer-reveals-details-of-anticipated-lady-gaga-episode/|title='Simpsons' Producer Reveals Details Of Anticipated Lady Gaga Episode|first=John|last=Mitchell|publisher=[[MTV]] ([[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]])|date=May 18, 2012|accessdate=May 20, 2012}}</ref> Due to the outfits' unconventional appearances, Jean was given more freedom to animate the large array of costumes, as these rapid changes \"wouldn't be possible in real life\".<ref name=mtv2/> \"There's a moment in the episode,\" Jean resumed, \"when she starts out with her hair down. Then, there's a curtain pulled in front of her, and in seconds, she has a completely different outfit on with a cone bra and her hair is all hairsprayed up and big and frizzy. In real life, that would probably take 8 hours.\"<ref name=mtv2/> Many of the costumes were inspired from previous outfits Gaga had worn, including [[Lady Gaga's meat dress|her meat dress]] and her [[Kermit the Frog]] dress. \"We did a lot of research, looking back at her old outfits, and she's really been in a million different things, had a million different looks.\"<ref name=mtv2/>\n\n==Cultural references==\nMany aspects of Gaga's career are referenced in the episode. \"You're All My Little Monsters\", a musical number specifically created for the episode,<ref name=mtv2/> is a parody of Gaga's relationship with her devout \"Little Monsters\"\u2014a phrase Gaga uses to refer to her fans.<ref name=bill/> To ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' columnist Devon Maloney, the song was ultimately an overtly cartoonized version of her single \"[[Born This Way (song)|Born This Way]]\" (2011) that embraces the \"freakiness\" of Springfield.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2012/05/hear-lady-gagas-cartoony-90-second-simpsons-tune/|title=Hear Lady Gaga's Cartoony, 90-Second 'Simpsons' Tune|first=Devon|last=Maloney|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|date=May 19, 2012|accessdate=May 23, 2012}}</ref> Several of Gaga's outfits and looks emulate several iconic costumes the singer had previously worn, such as the \"Living Dress\" and pyrotechnic leotard she wore during her endeavors on [[The Monster Ball Tour]], as well as her wardrobe at the [[53rd Grammy Awards]].<ref name=mtv22/> One in particular, a dress consisting of [[pork chops]], is a parody of the singer's [[Lady Gaga's meat dress|meat dress]], which she wore at the [[2010 MTV Video Music Awards]].<ref name=mtv2/> During the credits of \"Lisa Goes Gaga\", main character [[Homer Simpson]] performs a rendition of \"[[Poker Face (Lady Gaga song)|Poker Face]]\" (2009). At the end of the episode, a title card promotes the [[Maggie Simpson|Maggie]]-starring short film ''[[The Longest Daycare]]'', which was shown before ''[[Ice Age: Continental Drift]]'' (2012).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2012/05/22/the-simpsons-short-film/|title='The Simpsons': Exclusive details on the next big-screen adventure (it's short, silent, and in 3-D)!|first=Dan|last=Snierson|work=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=May 23, 2012|date=May 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\"Lisa Goes Gaga\" was originally broadcast on May 20, 2012 in the United States, as part of the \"[[Animation Domination]]\" television line-up on Fox. Upon airing, it acquired 4.79 million viewers and a 2.1 rating in the 18\u201349 demographic, indicating that 2.1 percent of individuals between ages 18 and 49 who watched television viewed the episode. \"Lisa Goes Gaga\" faced fierce competition, airing simultaneously with ''60 Minutes'' on [[CBS]], ''[[America's Got Talent]]'' on [[NBC]], and the [[Billboard Music Awards|2012 ''Billboard'' Music Awards]] on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]].<ref name=rating>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2012/05/21/tv-ratings-sunday-billboard-music-awards-leads-abc-to-nightly-win-family-guy-simpsons-celebrity-apprentice-finales-up/135161/|title=TV Ratings Sunday: 'Billboard Music Awards' Leads ABC to Nightly Win, 'Celebrity Apprentice' Sees Finale Low|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda|date=May 21, 2012|publisher=[[TV by the Numbers]]|accessdate=May 22, 2012}}</ref> Total viewership and ratings for the program evoked significant increases from the previous episode, \"[[Ned 'n Edna's Blend]]\", which attained 4.07 million viewers and a 1.9 rating in the 18\u201349 demographic, and also is the lowest rated episode to date in Nielsen Rating homes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2012/05/08/sunday-final-ratings-simpsons-amazing-race-finale-harrys-law-adjusted-up-desperate-housewives-nyc-22-adjusted-down/132865/|title=Sunday Final Ratings: 'Simpsons', 'Amazing Race' Finale, 'Harry's Law' Adjusted Up; 'Desperate Housewives', 'NYC 22' Adjusted Down|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda|date=May 8, 2012|publisher=[[TV by the Numbers]]|accessdate=May 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe episode produced varying responses from television commentators, and mostly mixed to negative reviews from viewers. \"Lisa Goes Gaga\" provoked ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' journalist Rowan Kaiser to conclude that the installment \"wasn't that painful to watch\"\u2014albeit found the concept and general execution to be irritating.<ref name=av/> In her B\u2013 review, Kaiser asserted that \"Lisa Goes Gaga\" used a straight-forward interpretation of the singer, and felt that Lady Gaga's appearance was superior to previous guest appearances. \"So many ''Simpsons'' celebrity voices,\" she stated, \"show up for a few minutes at most, with ''[[Extras (TV series)|Extras]]''-style 'Wow, [[Chris Martin]] of [[Coldplay]], what are you doing here?' Or they voice one-off characters without enough flair to be memorable. Instead, Gaga was the focus of the entire episode, to the point where if you wanted to call it a half-hour commercial for Lady Gaga, you probably wouldn\u2019t be wrong. Fortunately for 'Lisa Goes Gaga', the celebrity at its heart is entertaining enough that it being her commercial isn\u2019t a complete waste of time.\"<ref name=av>{{cite news|last=Kaiser|first=Rowan|title='Lisa Goes Gaga'|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/lisa-goes-gaga,75201/|accessdate=May 20, 2012|newspaper=[[The A.V. Club]]|date=May 20, 2012}}</ref> A writer for [[HLN (TV channel)|HLN]] avouched that ''The Simpsons'' managed to culminate its season \"with a lot of style\";<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hlntv.com/article/2012/05/21/lady-gaga-simpsons|title=Lisa Simpson now one of Lady Gaga's 'Monsters'!|publisher=[[HLN (TV channel)|HLN]]|date=May 21, 2012|accessdate=May 22, 2012}}</ref> David Greenwald of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' echoed similar sentiments.<Ref name=bill>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/news#/news/lady-gaga-s-simpsons-song-watch-1007117152.story|title=Lady Gaga's 'Simpsons' Song: Watch|first=David|last=Greenwald|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=May 22, 2012|accessdate=May 23, 2012}}</ref> Gaga's performance was frequently mentioned in the critiques. [[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]'s Becky Bain, Tracy Gilchrist of ''SheWired'', and Caroline Westbrook of ''[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]'' issued favorable assessments of her acting:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://idolator.com/6503991/lady-gaga-the-simpsons-little-monster-song|title=Lady Gaga Sings A Song To Her Little Monsters On \u2018The Simpsons\u2019|first=Becky|last=Bain|publisher=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]|date=May 21, 2012|accessdate=May 22, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shewired.com/box-office/2012/05/21/gaga-and-marge-simpson-make-out-watch|title=Gaga and Marge Simpson Make Out - Watch|first=Tracy|last=Gilchrist|work=SheWired|publisher=[[Here Media]]|date=May 21, 2012|accessdate=May 22, 2012}}</ref> the latter affirmed that Gaga had many memorable moments throughout the episode.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/tv/899738-lady-gaga-puckers-up-to-marge-as-she-appears-on-the-simpsons#ixzz1vZRw5H9k|title=Lady Gaga puckers up to Marge as she appears on The Simpsons|first=Caroline|last=Westbrook|work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|publisher=[[Associated Newspapers Ltd]]|date=May 21, 2012|accessdate=May 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\n{{quotation|And yet, as annoying as this episode was in concept and generally in execution, it wasn\u2019t that painful to actually watch. Cartoon Lady Gaga\u2019s costumes and theatricality were still entertaining. And even some of the Gaga-specific portions made me laugh, like Homer cooking Gaga\u2019s meat dress and eating it, or Bart dressing Maggie up as \u201cBaby Goo-goo.\u201d Against my better judgment, I was moderately entertained.|Rowan Kaiser|The A.V. Club<ref name=av/>}}\n\n\"The series did make good use of their guest star instead of reducing her role to a small cameo,\" opined ''TV Fanatic''{{'s}} Teresa L., who concluded: \"The episode ended up turning into one long-running gag about Gaga's eccentricities and a rehashing of all her most 'shocking' moments.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvfanatic.com/2012/05/the-simpsons-review-lady-blah-blah/#ixzz1vZdgtBTv|title=The Simpsons Review: Lady Blah-Blah|first=Teresa|last=L.|work=TV Fanatic|date=May 20, 2012|accessdate=May 22, 2012}}</ref> Jocelyn W. of ''TV Equals'' said, \"Lady Gaga helped ''The Simpsons'' end its 23rd season on a memorable note.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvequals.com/2012/05/21/the-simpsons-lisa-goes-gaga-review/|title=The Simpsons \u201cLisa Goes Gaga\u201d Review|first=Jocelyn|last=W.|publisher=TV Equals|date=May 21, 2012|accessdate=May 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Super Bowl LI halftime similarities==\nRight after Gaga performed in the [[Super Bowl LI halftime show]], many media outlets pointed out similarities between the beginning of the show where she descended from the roof of [[NRG Stadium]] from a harness to a similar scene in this episode in which she descends from a helicopter on a harness.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/the-simpsons-predicted-lady-gagas-super-bowl-performance_us_58985568e4b040613137bb82|title=\u2018The Simpsons\u2019 Predicted Lady Gaga\u2019s Super Bowl Halftime Show|first=Ron|last=Dicker|work=The Huffington Post|date=February 6, 2017|accessdate=February 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/02/the-simpsons-predicted-lady-gaga-super-bowl-halftime-show-2012-1201903217/|title=\u2018The Simpsons\u2019 Predicted Lady Gaga\u2019s Super Bowl Halftime Show In 2012|first=Denise|last=Petski|work=Deadline|date=February 6, 2017|accessdate=February 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7678106/remember-when-the-simpsons-totally-predicted-lady-gagas-super-bowl|title=Remember When 'The Simpsons' Totally Predicted Lady Gaga's Super Bowl Halftime Set?|first=Gil|last=Kaufman|work=Billboard|date=February 6, 2017|accessdate=February 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|The Simpsons}}\n*{{IMDb episode|id=2403733}}\n*{{Tv.com episode|2449228}}\n\n{{The Simpsons episodes|23}}\n{{Lady Gaga}}\n\n[[Category:2012 American television episodes]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Lady Gaga]]\n[[Category:The Simpsons (season 23) episodes]]\n[[Category:Television episodes about cyberbullying]]\n", "text_old": "{{Good article}}\n{{Infobox Simpsons episode\n| title          = Lisa Goes Gaga\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| season         = 23\n| episode        = 22 \n| director       = [[Matthew Schofield]]\n| writer         = [[Tim Long]]\n| production     = PABF14\n| airdate        = {{Start date|2012|05|20}}\n| guests         = [[Lady Gaga]] as herself<br/>[[Kevin Michael Richardson]] as Lady Gaga Express Conductor\n| blackboard     = \n| couch_gag      = The family are playing a [[Nintendo Wii|Zii]] game in which they sit on the couch, but Homer keeps failing. Homer angrily throws his controller down and tries to sit on the real couch, but fails just like in the game.\n| commentary     = \n| prev           = [[Ned 'n' Edna's Blend Agenda]]\n| next           = [[Moonshine River]]\n}}\n\"'''Lisa Goes Gaga'''\" is the twenty-second and final episode of the [[The Simpsons (season 23)|twenty-third season]] of the American animated sitcom ''[[The Simpsons]]''. It originally aired on the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox network]] in the United States on May 20, 2012. In the episode, American singer-songwriter [[Lady Gaga]] makes a visit to Springfield, where all of its residents are in a state of depression. Main character [[Lisa Simpson]] is arguably the most depressed person in the city, prompting Gaga to go out of her way to teach Lisa the meaning of happiness.\n\nThe episode was written by [[Tim Long]] and directed by Matthew Schofield. Gaga guest-starred in the episode, portraying an animated version of herself. A fan of the show, she was brought on by showrunner [[Al Jean]], who wrote a script after [[James L. Brooks]] saw an interview of her on ''[[60 Minutes]]''. The design team conceived eighteen outfits to complement Gaga's eccentric persona, which satirized several of her outfits including her [[Lady Gaga's meat dress|meat dress]]. Recording sessions for \"Lisa Goes Gaga\" took place in [[Los Angeles, California]] over four days in August 2011. \n\nCritical responses to the episode were mixed to negative; critics praised Lady Gaga's performance, while they looked down upon the episode's concept and general execution. According to the [[Nielsen ratings]], the installment attained 4.79 million American viewers upon its original airing.\n\n==Plot==\n[[Lady Gaga]] passes through [[Springfield (The Simpsons)|Springfield]] via train while on her way to a concert.  Seeing how low the city's self-esteem is, she takes it upon herself to cheer up the whole city. However, no one in town is more depressed than [[Lisa Simpson|Lisa]], who was voted as the most unpopular student by her peers. Lisa tries to reverse her status as one of the least popular girls in school by ghostwriting positive things about herself on the school blog under the heading \"Truth Teller\".\n\nWhen [[Bart Simpson|Bart]] finds out her secret and reveals it to the school, her social ranking plummets to a new low until a psychic force tells Lady Gaga that Lisa needs her help immediately. After much soul searching and yelling at Lady Gaga for trying to help, Lisa realizes that her outburst helped her because she is finally expressing her anger instead of bottling it up inside her, in effect making Lady Gaga's mission successful. Lisa catches Lady Gaga just before she leaves town to apologize, and after being forgiven she and Lady Gaga perform a duet together. With Lady Gaga's assistance, Lisa and the entire town of Springfield realize that being oneself is better than being like anyone else. Just as Lady Gaga's train begins to leave again, [[Moe Szyslak|Moe]] runs up to her and asks if she can help him as well, but Lady Gaga declines, stating that she's not that good. As Moe turns and walks across the train track, a second train hits him.<!--He appears in the following episode alive, \"Moonshine River\"-->\n\nDuring the credits, Homer is heard singing his rendition of \"[[Poker Face (Lady Gaga song)|Poker Face]]\".\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Gaga pyro bra 02.jpg|thumb|Gaga's Pyrotechnic Underwear was one of her outfits that was parodied in the episode.]]\n\nIn August 2011, it first was revealed that [[Lady Gaga]] would make a guest appearance on the show as herself.<ref name=EW>{{cite web|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2011/08/23/lady-gaga-the-simpsons-exclusive-photo/?iid=rcfooter-tv-%27simpsons%27+goes+gaga%3A+first+pic!|title=Lady Gaga to guest on 'The Simpsons' -- Exclusive Photo|last=Snierson|first= Dan|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time, Inc.]]|date=August 23, 2011|accessdate=August 23, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/news/lady-gaga-to-spice-up-the-simpsons-16041045.html|title=Lady Gaga to spice up The Simpsons|work=[[The Belfast Telegraph]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|date=August 25, 2011|accessdate=August 26, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/celebritology/post/lady-gaga-gets-animated-for-the-simpsons/2011/08/23/gIQA3B2CZJ_blog.html|title=Lady Gaga gets animated for \u2018The Simpsons\u2019|first=Sarah|last=Anne Hughes|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=August 23, 2011|accessdate=August 26, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/08/23/lady-gaga-to-guest-star-the-simpsons_n_934423.html|title=Lady Gaga To Guest-Star On 'The Simpsons'|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|publisher=[[Arianna Huffington]]|date=August 23, 2011|accessdate=August 26, 2011}}</ref> Producer [[James L. Brooks]] viewed Gaga's interview with [[Anderson Cooper]] on ''[[60 Minutes]]'', which prompted [[Al Jean]] to write a script and send her a letter of approval to appear on the show.<ref name=mtv2>{{cite web|url=http://style.mtv.com/2012/05/18/lady-gaga-the-simpsons/|title=Lady Gaga's 'The Simpsons' Style: Exclusive Interview With Executive Producer/Writer Al Jean|first=Gaby|last=Wilson|publisher=[[MTV]] ([[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]])|date=May 18, 2012|accessdate=May 20, 2012}}</ref> \"She was really excited about the whole thing,\" Jean recalled. \"After she signed on to do it, she came in to record dialogue twice, and we showed her a rough cut the second time.\"<ref name=mtv2/> Recording sessions for the episode took place in [[Los Angeles]] during a period of four days from August 22\u201326.<ref name=EW/> Gaga was initially apprehensive while recording on set, which led her to review the satirical nature of the show to get a better understanding on how to perform. \"Their characters are so awesomely convincing and sincere and wild and funny, I had to remind myself constantly of the sincerity of the humor,\" she explained. \"That's what I was trying to focus on\u2014not putting on a character too much, and really being as sincere as I could with the lines.\"<ref name=EW/> Despite such emotions, Gaga professed that working with the staff of the show was \"one of the coolest things that [she] has ever done\".<ref name=EW/>\n\nSeveral employees of ''The Simpsons'' were impressed with Gaga's performance, who cited that her vocal range and ad-libbing skills were exceptional. Series creator [[Matt Groening]] stated: \"Since the very beginning, I\u2019ve always wanted to have on the most iconic personalities of our time, and she's it.\"<ref name=EW/> In an interview with [[E! Online]], Groening further commented on Gaga's appearance; \"The great thing about having Lady Gaga is that she came in a number of times and always with a different getup. Like she'd leave the room and come back in after a break in a completely new getup. It was unbelievable. The only time that she ever took off her hat was when it was banging into the microphone.\"<ref name=e!>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/watch_with_kristin/jennifer_aniston_really_coming_cougar/193233 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20121208190236/http://www.eonline.com/news/watch_with_kristin/jennifer_aniston_really_coming_cougar/193233 |url-status=dead |archive-date=December 8, 2012 |title=The Simpsons Celebrates 500 Episodes: How Kooky Was Lady Gaga? And Which Big Stars Are Next? |first=Tierney |last=Bricker |publisher=[[E!]] |date=February 17, 2012 |accessdate=February 18, 2012 }}</ref> Cast member [[Yeardley Smith]] said that she was shocked that Gaga had the time to make an appearance on the series.<ref name=MTV>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1669502/lady-gaga-the-simpsons-guest.jhtml|title=Lady Gaga To Guest-Star On 'The Simpsons'|first=Jocelyn|last=Vena|publisher=[[MTV]] ([[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]])|date=August 23, 2011|accessdate=August 23, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe design team for the series conceived eighteen outfits to complement Gaga's [[wiktionary:outr\u00e9|outr\u00e9]] and eccentric reputation, although they did not collaborate with any of Gaga's stylists or creative director [[Nicola Formichetti]].<ref name=mtv22>{{cite web|url=http://newsroom.mtv.com/2012/05/18/simpsons-producer-reveals-details-of-anticipated-lady-gaga-episode/|title='Simpsons' Producer Reveals Details Of Anticipated Lady Gaga Episode|first=John|last=Mitchell|publisher=[[MTV]] ([[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]])|date=May 18, 2012|accessdate=May 20, 2012}}</ref> Due to the outfits' unconventional appearances, Jean was given more freedom to animate the large array of costumes, as these rapid changes \"wouldn't be possible in real life\".<ref name=mtv2/> \"There's a moment in the episode,\" Jean resumed, \"when she starts out with her hair down. Then, there's a curtain pulled in front of her, and in seconds, she has a completely different outfit on with a cone bra and her hair is all hairsprayed up and big and frizzy. In real life, that would probably take 8 hours.\"<ref name=mtv2/> Many of the costumes were inspired from previous outfits Gaga had worn, including [[Lady Gaga's meat dress|her meat dress]] and her [[Kermit the Frog]] dress. \"We did a lot of research, looking back at her old outfits, and she's really been in a million different things, had a million different looks.\"<ref name=mtv2/>\n\n==Cultural references==\nMany aspects of Gaga's career are referenced in the episode. \"You're All My Little Monsters\", a musical number specifically created for the episode,<ref name=mtv2/> is a parody of Gaga's relationship with her devout \"Little Monsters\"\u2014a phrase Gaga uses to refer to her fans.<ref name=bill/> To ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' columnist Devon Maloney, the song was ultimately an overtly cartoonized version of her single \"[[Born This Way (song)|Born This Way]]\" (2011) that embraces the \"freakiness\" of Springfield.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2012/05/hear-lady-gagas-cartoony-90-second-simpsons-tune/|title=Hear Lady Gaga's Cartoony, 90-Second 'Simpsons' Tune|first=Devon|last=Maloney|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|date=May 19, 2012|accessdate=May 23, 2012}}</ref> Several of Gaga's outfits and looks emulate several iconic costumes the singer had previously worn, such as the \"Living Dress\" and pyrotechnic leotard she wore during her endeavors on [[The Monster Ball Tour]], as well as her wardrobe at the [[53rd Grammy Awards]].<ref name=mtv22/> One in particular, a dress consisting of [[pork chops]], is a parody of the singer's [[Lady Gaga's meat dress|meat dress]], which she wore at the [[2010 MTV Video Music Awards]].<ref name=mtv2/> During the credits of \"Lisa Goes Gaga\", main character [[Homer Simpson]] performs a rendition of \"[[Poker Face (Lady Gaga song)|Poker Face]]\" (2009). At the end of the episode, a title card promotes the [[Maggie Simpson|Maggie]]-starring short film ''[[The Longest Daycare]]'', which was shown before ''[[Ice Age: Continental Drift]]'' (2012).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2012/05/22/the-simpsons-short-film/|title='The Simpsons': Exclusive details on the next big-screen adventure (it's short, silent, and in 3-D)!|first=Dan|last=Snierson|work=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=May 23, 2012|date=May 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\"Lisa Goes Gaga\" was originally broadcast on May 20, 2012 in the United States, as part of the \"[[Animation Domination]]\" television line-up on Fox. Upon airing, it acquired 4.79 million viewers and a 2.1 rating in the 18\u201349 demographic, indicating that 2.1 percent of individuals between ages 18 and 49 who watched television viewed the episode. \"Lisa Goes Gaga\" faced fierce competition, airing simultaneously with ''60 Minutes'' on [[CBS]], ''[[America's Got Talent]]'' on [[NBC]], and the [[Billboard Music Awards|2012 ''Billboard'' Music Awards]] on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]].<ref name=rating>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2012/05/21/tv-ratings-sunday-billboard-music-awards-leads-abc-to-nightly-win-family-guy-simpsons-celebrity-apprentice-finales-up/135161/|title=TV Ratings Sunday: 'Billboard Music Awards' Leads ABC to Nightly Win, 'Celebrity Apprentice' Sees Finale Low|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda|date=May 21, 2012|publisher=[[TV by the Numbers]]|accessdate=May 22, 2012}}</ref> Total viewership and ratings for the program evoked significant increases from the previous episode, \"[[Ned 'n Edna's Blend]]\", which attained 4.07 million viewers and a 1.9 rating in the 18\u201349 demographic, and also is the lowest rated episode to date in Nielsen Rating homes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2012/05/08/sunday-final-ratings-simpsons-amazing-race-finale-harrys-law-adjusted-up-desperate-housewives-nyc-22-adjusted-down/132865/|title=Sunday Final Ratings: 'Simpsons', 'Amazing Race' Finale, 'Harry's Law' Adjusted Up; 'Desperate Housewives', 'NYC 22' Adjusted Down|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda|date=May 8, 2012|publisher=[[TV by the Numbers]]|accessdate=May 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe episode produced varying responses from television commentators, and mostly mixed to negative reviews from viewers. \"Lisa Goes Gaga\" provoked ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' journalist Rowan Kaiser to conclude that the installment \"wasn't that painful to watch\"\u2014albeit found the concept and general execution to be irritating.<ref name=av/> In her B\u2013 review, Kaiser asserted that \"Lisa Goes Gaga\" used a straight-forward interpretation of the singer, and felt that Lady Gaga's appearance was superior to previous guest appearances. \"So many ''Simpsons'' celebrity voices,\" she stated, \"show up for a few minutes at most, with ''[[Extras (TV series)|Extras]]''-style 'Wow, [[Chris Martin]] of [[Coldplay]], what are you doing here?' Or they voice one-off characters without enough flair to be memorable. Instead, Gaga was the focus of the entire episode, to the point where if you wanted to call it a half-hour commercial for Lady Gaga, you probably wouldn\u2019t be wrong. Fortunately for 'Lisa Goes Gaga', the celebrity at its heart is entertaining enough that it being her commercial isn\u2019t a complete waste of time.\"<ref name=av>{{cite news|last=Kaiser|first=Rowan|title='Lisa Goes Gaga'|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/lisa-goes-gaga,75201/|accessdate=May 20, 2012|newspaper=[[The A.V. Club]]|date=May 20, 2012}}</ref> A writer for [[HLN (TV channel)|HLN]] avouched that ''The Simpsons'' managed to culminate its season \"with a lot of style\";<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hlntv.com/article/2012/05/21/lady-gaga-simpsons|title=Lisa Simpson now one of Lady Gaga's 'Monsters'!|publisher=[[HLN (TV channel)|HLN]]|date=May 21, 2012|accessdate=May 22, 2012}}</ref> David Greenwald of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' echoed similar sentiments.<Ref name=bill>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/news#/news/lady-gaga-s-simpsons-song-watch-1007117152.story|title=Lady Gaga's 'Simpsons' Song: Watch|first=David|last=Greenwald|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=May 22, 2012|accessdate=May 23, 2012}}</ref> Gaga's performance was frequently mentioned in the critiques. [[Idolator]]'s Becky Bain, Tracy Gilchrist of ''SheWired'', and Caroline Westbrook of ''[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]'' issued favorable assessments of her acting:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://idolator.com/6503991/lady-gaga-the-simpsons-little-monster-song|title=Lady Gaga Sings A Song To Her Little Monsters On \u2018The Simpsons\u2019|first=Becky|last=Bain|publisher=[[Idolator]]|date=May 21, 2012|accessdate=May 22, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shewired.com/box-office/2012/05/21/gaga-and-marge-simpson-make-out-watch|title=Gaga and Marge Simpson Make Out - Watch|first=Tracy|last=Gilchrist|work=SheWired|publisher=[[Here Media]]|date=May 21, 2012|accessdate=May 22, 2012}}</ref> the latter affirmed that Gaga had many memorable moments throughout the episode.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/tv/899738-lady-gaga-puckers-up-to-marge-as-she-appears-on-the-simpsons#ixzz1vZRw5H9k|title=Lady Gaga puckers up to Marge as she appears on The Simpsons|first=Caroline|last=Westbrook|work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|publisher=[[Associated Newspapers Ltd]]|date=May 21, 2012|accessdate=May 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\n{{quotation|And yet, as annoying as this episode was in concept and generally in execution, it wasn\u2019t that painful to actually watch. Cartoon Lady Gaga\u2019s costumes and theatricality were still entertaining. And even some of the Gaga-specific portions made me laugh, like Homer cooking Gaga\u2019s meat dress and eating it, or Bart dressing Maggie up as \u201cBaby Goo-goo.\u201d Against my better judgment, I was moderately entertained.|Rowan Kaiser|The A.V. Club<ref name=av/>}}\n\n\"The series did make good use of their guest star instead of reducing her role to a small cameo,\" opined ''TV Fanatic''{{'s}} Teresa L., who concluded: \"The episode ended up turning into one long-running gag about Gaga's eccentricities and a rehashing of all her most 'shocking' moments.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvfanatic.com/2012/05/the-simpsons-review-lady-blah-blah/#ixzz1vZdgtBTv|title=The Simpsons Review: Lady Blah-Blah|first=Teresa|last=L.|work=TV Fanatic|date=May 20, 2012|accessdate=May 22, 2012}}</ref> Jocelyn W. of ''TV Equals'' said, \"Lady Gaga helped ''The Simpsons'' end its 23rd season on a memorable note.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvequals.com/2012/05/21/the-simpsons-lisa-goes-gaga-review/|title=The Simpsons \u201cLisa Goes Gaga\u201d Review|first=Jocelyn|last=W.|publisher=TV Equals|date=May 21, 2012|accessdate=May 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Super Bowl LI halftime similarities==\nRight after Gaga performed in the [[Super Bowl LI halftime show]], many media outlets pointed out similarities between the beginning of the show where she descended from the roof of [[NRG Stadium]] from a harness to a similar scene in this episode in which she descends from a helicopter on a harness.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/the-simpsons-predicted-lady-gagas-super-bowl-performance_us_58985568e4b040613137bb82|title=\u2018The Simpsons\u2019 Predicted Lady Gaga\u2019s Super Bowl Halftime Show|first=Ron|last=Dicker|work=The Huffington Post|date=February 6, 2017|accessdate=February 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/02/the-simpsons-predicted-lady-gaga-super-bowl-halftime-show-2012-1201903217/|title=\u2018The Simpsons\u2019 Predicted Lady Gaga\u2019s Super Bowl Halftime Show In 2012|first=Denise|last=Petski|work=Deadline|date=February 6, 2017|accessdate=February 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7678106/remember-when-the-simpsons-totally-predicted-lady-gagas-super-bowl|title=Remember When 'The Simpsons' Totally Predicted Lady Gaga's Super Bowl Halftime Set?|first=Gil|last=Kaufman|work=Billboard|date=February 6, 2017|accessdate=February 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|The Simpsons}}\n*{{IMDb episode|id=2403733}}\n*{{Tv.com episode|2449228}}\n\n{{The Simpsons episodes|23}}\n{{Lady Gaga}}\n\n[[Category:2012 American television episodes]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Lady Gaga]]\n[[Category:The Simpsons (season 23) episodes]]\n[[Category:Television episodes about cyberbullying]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toIdolator(link changed toIdolator (website); link changed toIdolator (website)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lisa_Goes_Gaga"}
{"title_page": "Vito Da Ros", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Vito Da Ros\n| image         =\n| caption       =\n| fullname      = \n| nickname      =\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1957|5|31|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Caneva]], [[Italy]]\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| height        =\n| weight        =\n| currentteam   =\n| discipline    =\n| role          =\n| ridertype     =\n| amateuryears1 =\n| amateurteam1  =\n| proyears1     =\n| proteam1      =\n| majorwins     =\n| updated       = \n}}\n\n'''Vito Da Ros''' (born 31 May 1957) is an Italian former [[cycling|cyclist]]. He competed in the [[Cycling at the 1976 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's team time trial|team time trial]] event at the [[1976 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/da/vito-da-ros-1.html |title=Vito Da Ros Olympic Results |accessdate=25 April 2015 |work=Sports Reference}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Da Ros, Vito}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of Italy]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1976 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Friuli-Venezia Giulia]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Pordenone]]\n{{Italy-cycling-bio-1950s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Vito Da Ros\n| image         =\n| caption       =\n| fullname      = \n| nickname      =\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1957|5|31|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Caneva]], [[Italy]]\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| height        =\n| weight        =\n| currentteam   =\n| discipline    =\n| role          =\n| ridertype     =\n| amateuryears1 =\n| amateurteam1  =\n| proyears1     =\n| proteam1      =\n| majorwins     =\n| updated       = 